WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-IN

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.000 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:04.280 line:1%
…then you have to go to an airport
and a burger shop.

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:05.921 line:1%
[loud laughter]

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:09.600
Marriages, for example,
two seasons in India, both harvesting.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:12.281
Post harvesting, marriage starts.
Because that's the resource for them.

00:00:12.361 --> 00:00:14.400
So people are just discovering something

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:16.361
and saying, "Hey, this looks cool.
I wanna buy this."

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:18.360
[Nikhil] What are you saying, in summary?

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:20.960
Like, if I am building a product
for today, what is that insight?

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:24.800
I have seen children of abundant families
doing phenomenally well,

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:27.640
and building new categories
and new products.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:35.160
The first thing we were talking about
before you arrived is,

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:38.800
"Are the products from your e-commerce
company as late as you arrived?"

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.560
-Like…
-[laughter]

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:46.640 line:1%
This is not correct.

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:48.160
We're kidding.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:49.760
We won't put this part in the podcast.

00:00:49.840 --> 00:00:52.041
-[Vidit sighs]
-[Sujeet] That's fair, he…

00:00:52.121 --> 00:00:53.880
He's saying that he was late
because he was managing on time.

00:00:53.961 --> 00:00:55.520
[Vidit laughs]

00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:01.760
So, hi, guys.
Welcome, everyone, to Episode 3.

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:05.160
Uh, I think, to begin,
maybe we can all, like,

00:01:05.240 --> 00:01:07.440
speak about what we do in one minute.

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:11.760
And since we all know
each other already, uh,

00:01:11.841 --> 00:01:15.560
we can intersect and we can say
different things we know about each other.

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:18.880
The idea is just to get everybody
to know who we are.

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:20.840
So, let's start with Vidit.

00:01:22.441 --> 00:01:24.920
Hey, I'm Vidit Aatrey. I run Meesho.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:26.760
-Meesho is…
-[Nikhil] Not like that.

00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:28.640
Not what you give
in college interviews and stuff.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:30.320 line:1%
What do you say, then?

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:31.600 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:34.720
"I am Vidit. I was born here.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:37.040
"I was this kind of a child."

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.280
Yes, that's exactly
what the college interview is.

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:41.640
[Nikhil] "You know, at this age…"

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:42.840
[Sujeet chuckles]

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:48.880 line:1%
So I have to give something
different, right?

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:50.360 line:1%
[Sujeet] Yeah, yeah.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:54.000
[Nikhil] Basically, you have to say
the absolute blatant truth.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:56.640
We were saying that, like,
anybody would find about your…

00:01:56.721 --> 00:02:00.520
Like, who you are…
Something which is not on… Yeah.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:03.520
It's a good point.
So, I… Hey, I'm Vidit Aatrey.

00:02:03.601 --> 00:02:05.320
I grew up in Delhi,

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:08.760
in that part of Delhi that people
don't know as much, which is Rohini.

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:13.240
I was born in Meerut, so my entire family
comes from Meerut and Hapur.

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:17.440
So… I was the first engineer
in my entire family, right?

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:19.440
-So it's a…
-What was everyone else doing?

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:22.165
Farming. Both, my mom and dad's side,
like, everyone.

00:02:22.245 --> 00:02:24.840
Like, all my cousins,
most of them still do farming.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.520
And… So, it was
a very different upbringing.

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:29.880
When I was growing up,
my dad used to tell me,

00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:31.760
"There are only two kinds of professions.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:35.960 line:1%
"One, someone who does a government job.
"Second, who sits in a parchun ki dukaan.

00:02:36.040 --> 00:02:38.320 line:1%
"So, if you don't want to sit
in a parchun ki dukaan, you better study."

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:41.841
-What is a parchun ki dukaan?
-[Vidit] It is a grocery store, basically.

00:02:41.921 --> 00:02:43.706
"So, if you don't want to sit there,

00:02:43.786 --> 00:02:46.458
"you better study
and become an IAS officer someday."

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:48.760
So, all my life, I was told this.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:51.080
And I used to believe it
for a very long time.

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:56.200
And I grew up, went to IIT-Delhi,
all of that.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:59.360
When I went there, I realized the world
is not bipolar, "only two professions",

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:02.361
and there's a lot more
other things you can do.

00:03:02.441 --> 00:03:04.201
And that's when I changed.

00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:09.120
Um, after college, went
to, um… went to ITC

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:11.480
in an operations heavy role.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:15.600
Very different. And from Delhi to Chennai.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:18.560
And I went into a factory where the…

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.040
where everyone in the factory
used to speak only one language,

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:22.560
which was Tamil.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:26.120
And I used to…
I used to go everyday in the office,

00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:28.480
there used to be a morning
stand-up meeting,

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:31.160
which was about an hour, in Tamil.

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:33.160
[Sujeet chuckles softly]

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.040
And I'm standing there…
Like, everyone knows English.

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:37.441
I'm saying, "Why don't we speak English?"

00:03:37.521 --> 00:03:39.600
"Because we are in Chennai,
so we have to speak in Tamil."

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:43.400
So, I used to stand there
and have no idea what's happening.

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:45.640
But I was forced to, kind of,
pick up some bit.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:50.880
I would say, like, the first two years
of my career, it was very interesting,

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:53.560
because I was put
into the most uncomfortable parts.

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:57.321
Like, you sitting in Delhi,
you can do all the nice stuff.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:59.560
Like you can do good analysis
if you understand Excel,

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:01.840
but managing a lot of people,

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:04.720
going to a place where
you're uncomfortable about everything:

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:06.480
language, food.

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:09.640
Over time, figuring out
your way around this.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:12.960
But I think it was…
it was pretty cool, if I look back.

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:16.520
At that point of time, I got connected
to a friend who was in Bangalore,

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.160
Bangalore was coming up,

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:21.040
like your Flipkarts
and your InMobis of the world.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:22.440
So I moved here.

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:24.600
-And, eventually, in 2015…
-You guys are from the same college, no?

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.720
Yeah, yeah, same college,
but I think the…

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:29.640
-In which year did you pass out?
-2012.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.640
Yeah, he is, like,
nine years junior to me.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.320
Yeah. It's much, much later.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:38.880
So, yeah. So I think then I come to…
came to Bangalore, and…

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.120
like, everyone else,
got bitten by the entrepreneurial bug

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:44.480
because there was so much to do.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:47.080
Then, we started Meesho back in 2015.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.560
Um, so, now, coming to, like,
what we do at Meesho

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:54.680
and why did we even pick
what we are doing…

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:57.120
So, we started in 2015,

00:04:57.200 --> 00:04:59.800
and doing this because we realized
that e-commerce was coming up

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.000
and everyone was talking about,
"Hey, why…"

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:04.800
How all of this was moving online.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:07.280
But e-commerce at that point of time

00:05:07.360 --> 00:05:09.680
was mostly smartphones
and white goods selling online, right?

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:12.920
Like, which was not "India retail"
to some extent.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.440
Small businesses were a very core part
of India retail,

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:17.000
but still primarily offline.

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:19.016
And 85% of India retail happens via

00:05:19.096 --> 00:05:22.080
a lot of these long tail,
unbranded small businesses.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:24.080
So we said, "We'll bring them online."

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:27.760
If someone asked me "how", I had no idea,
but we said we'll bring them online.

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:29.640
And that's when we started Meesho.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:34.280
So, yeah, we'll complete eight years.
Been a very, very interesting journey.

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:39.720
Um, now we have close to
140 million consumers who buy from us

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:42.240
annually across all kinds of categories

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:44.840
from about a million small businesses.

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:48.800
-So… that's all.
-[Nikhil] Hmm.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:50.160
Super.

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:55.520
So, uh, I think Mr. Kishore Biyani,
everybody knows.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:01.240
Broadly, you're an icon of selling,
both online and offline.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:05.200
And I think each one of us, growing up,
in one way or another,

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:08.800
has some way, in one way or another,

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.640
experienced one product
that you might have made or another.

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:16.040
So maybe, even though we have seen you,

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:20.880
we don't know so much about
your childhood, where you were born.

00:06:20.961 --> 00:06:23.161
I've met your family,
I've come to your house.

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:25.920
I've met your daughters
and stuff like that.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.840
But, uh, maybe you can
give us a minute or two?

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:30.880
Yeah. So, I'm Kishore Biyani.

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:37.200
I've formed a lot of consumer businesses,
called our group the Future Group.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:40.280
Uh… [clears throat] I was born in Bombay.

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:42.640
Born and brought up in Bombay.

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:45.640
Studied commerce…

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.000
I was interested in marketing.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:53.880
So, used to follow most of the advertising
that used to happen then.

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:57.400
And then, built my own brand of trousers
to start with.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:06:58.960
Started with the fabric business…

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.920
How did you first
think of starting a trouser brand?

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.640
I think that was way back, and…

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:06.120
[Sujeet] Which year?

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:07.320
[Kishore] I would say…

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:10.360
'91 or something?

00:07:11.601 --> 00:07:13.360
I was supplying garments…

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:15.200
I was supplying fabric
to the garment industry.

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:17.280
At that time, the brands were
Charagh Din, Double Bull.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:19.120
They were very different brands then.

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:21.640
-[Nikhil] What year was this?
-This must be '87.

00:07:23.041 --> 00:07:26.480
And people were just moving into,
from tailor-made to ready-made.

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:28.601
-[Nikhil] Vidit was not even born.
-[Vidit] Yeah.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:30.760
[laughter]

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:34.320
I feel odd one out here
in terms of seniority.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:37.920
-[Sujeet chuckling]
-He… he's half way there.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.800
I'm a little bit lower, he's the youngest.

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:43.880
It was a different world, I was born
to a very conservative family.

00:07:43.960 --> 00:07:46.200
We come from Rajasthan.

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:49.840
Family was very religious, pious,
I was an atheist…

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:53.800
Always, what do you call? I was known
as the black sheep of the family.

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:57.080
And contrarian thoughts
on everything in life.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:01.520
And, so… I thought
I'll not join the family business,

00:08:01.600 --> 00:08:05.360
we had a small wholesale
fabric trading business that time.

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:08.040
So when I joined… When I just graduated,

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:10.880
I did some course in marketing,
I did my…

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:13.040
I did my CA entrance.

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.880
I never… I think,
in five years of college,

00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:19.040
I went to attend a class only once.

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:21.320
One class attended in five years.

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:26.600
Do you think there is some kind of
a correlation between rebellious kids

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:31.520
or kids who have grown up
with more insecurity than usual

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:33.600
to how well they do later in life?

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:37.680
Do you think more rebellious, insecure
end up doing better?

00:08:38.920 --> 00:08:43.000
I believe that, today,
my children are born in abundance

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:45.160
and to more democratic parents.

00:08:45.241 --> 00:08:49.480
I was not born to democratic parents,
and we were born in the shortage era.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:53.842
So, I think shortages
or less availability

00:08:53.922 --> 00:08:56.416
does definitely make you work harder,

00:08:56.496 --> 00:08:59.400
and make you expand
your mind and thoughts.

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:02.320
So, I think abundance
can create something else,

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:05.640
but what we got was not abundance
in any which way.

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:08.000
He also doesn't come from abundance,
in a way, no?

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:11.240
I don't. And, by the way, to some extent,

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:14.640
I agree with what you were just asking.
I believe…

00:09:16.160 --> 00:09:18.080
Like I come from a family
where I would say

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:20.521
even when I was growing up,
I was a very compliant child.

00:09:20.601 --> 00:09:22.960
So, whatever my parents tell me, I do it.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:26.960
Until I come to college, and suddenly
I have an independent bent of mind.

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:28.325
Now I question everything.

00:09:28.405 --> 00:09:29.909
So, until then, I would say, like,

00:09:29.989 --> 00:09:32.240
my parents would make me do that pooja
every day.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:34.080
And I am an atheist since college.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:37.160
Right? So everything changed.
Because, until then,

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:40.058
right, like, I only saw
a very small part of the world,

00:09:40.138 --> 00:09:44.120
and I thought this is right and wrong,
and everything is very black and white.

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:46.240
And as you get exposed
to more and more stuff,

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:48.040
then some people are okay,

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:50.840
and you can say rebellious,
I call it independent.

00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:52.800
But I feel it happens,

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:57.281
and it's definitely one input
to doing something crazy, right?

00:09:57.361 --> 00:09:59.200
Because if you do something
which is by the book,

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:02.720
it's very hard for you to challenge
what has been happening for years.

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:06.400
But only thing I observed that is common.

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:09.640
Like, he passed out in 2012,

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:12.441
and you are somewhere in '80.

00:10:12.521 --> 00:10:16.320
But still, the feeling
of, like, I have grown

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:19.320
in such a constrained, disciplined family…

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:24.080
Because how I see,
and might be that's not the truth,

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:28.960
but children, these days,
we say, "No, they have a lot."

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:33.120
Might be that you have the same feeling,
"Hey, a 2012 kid has a lot of access

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:37.520
"to information, infrastructure,
better college, better education."

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:41.201
But the feeling is similar.
And it doesn't matter…

00:10:41.281 --> 00:10:47.880
Like, my grandfather was always saying
that when I was studying,

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:50.160
I was crossing river,
walking this much kilometers,

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:51.240
and things like that.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:54.281
And when we were studying,
he was saying, "You guys have everything."

00:10:54.361 --> 00:10:57.240
And we believe,
"No, no, this is also tough."

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:59.840
[chuckles] So I think that feeling
is very common.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:01.360
-That is my…
-Do you think that is true?

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.918
Like, say, my parents…
my mom was a music teacher,

00:11:03.998 --> 00:11:05.520
and my dad was a bank employee.

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:10.037
But do you think people who grew up
in middle-class upbringing,

00:11:10.117 --> 00:11:11.840
like myself, or under,

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:16.160
feel more insecure about things
like money,

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:20.320
things like having the freedom
that can be associated with money,

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:23.120
and hence they over-compensate
when they grow older?

00:11:24.041 --> 00:11:27.320
I think money matters a bit lesser here.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:28.600
Like I…

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:32.680
It's obviously when I was growing up,
coming from a lower-middle class family,

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:36.400
like, if… It's a very top-of-mind
thing to solve.

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:38.520
But I don't think that leads to it.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:42.200
Like, very hard for me to attribute to it.

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:44.520
-[Nikhil] Right.
-If we go by data, it's very hard.

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:46.520
Might be we can share our perspective,

00:11:46.600 --> 00:11:49.880
from the rebellious point-of-view,
but I think that's not true.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:53.080
I think it was very regimental in nature
when you're middle-class,

00:11:53.160 --> 00:11:55.840
"Hey, you have to study.
There is only one way.

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:58.400
"You have to get a… Like,
get into some job.

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:00.520
"Nice job, otherwise your marriage
will not happen."

00:12:00.600 --> 00:12:03.240
Things like that. I think those
are the main issues.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:07.280
Might be for us, it was never that issue,
and so that's why you can…

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:09.800
But, by data, I'll tell you we all invest
in start-ups, right?

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:11.400
Like, each one of us.

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:14.640
Uh, I didn't realize this for a long time,

00:12:14.720 --> 00:12:18.360
but very organically you…
at least we formed a filter.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.760
By "we," I mean different funds
I'm a part of,

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:25.001
that if somebody was a very entitled guy,

00:12:25.081 --> 00:12:29.280
if somebody was the son
or a daughter of a very rich man,

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:33.160
you would have this thing
in your subconscious

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:36.240
which would make you wary of investing
in that start-up.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:39.640
-Same. I've had the same thing.
-It's not true, in a way.

00:12:40.561 --> 00:12:42.840
I believe it's nature of a…

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:46.680
But he can excel in something else
which nobody else can do.

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:49.000
Some categories,
they can excel much, much better.

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:51.720
So I… We have dwelt a lot
into understanding this,

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:54.680
but I think
abundance creates something else

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.480
and shortages create something else.

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:58.640
But rebelliousness definitely
creates something.

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:01.200
Without being a rebel, you can't…

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.520
Because as a rebellion,

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:04.800
you like to destroy something
and create something.

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:07.200
Now I got into… I created…

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:10.480
I went into business, created a fabric
which became quite popular,

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:12.200
it was called stonewash at that time.

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:14.320
Then, denim as a fabric came in.

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:15.800
How did you create this fabric?

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:19.680
I think… I think there was a fashion
which was going along.

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:22.229
And I was… I did some course in weaving,

00:13:22.309 --> 00:13:25.280
and I was very interested
in textile fabric as such.

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:26.520
So…

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.400
How old were you
when you were doing this course?

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:30.000
[Kishore] Twenty-one, twenty-two?

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:32.106
Was it a thing back then,
to do a course in weaving

00:13:32.186 --> 00:13:33.240
and try to make a fabric?

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:34.841
I was trying to do everything.

00:13:34.921 --> 00:13:39.160
I was not a great student
or had inclination toward studies.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:42.080
My parents never knew
whether I passed or failed also.

00:13:42.881 --> 00:13:45.200
So… So we were a joint family.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:47.440
We were 13 of us in our age group.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:49.680
My father had six brothers.

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:54.160
And if we all came and one of them
didn't sleep also, nobody would notice.

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:56.400
We lived very, very differently then.

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:02.320
I think, uh…
So, the idea was to create something.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:05.640
And it started with creating that fabric,
supplying to the garment industry,

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:07.920
building denim, then building
our own brand.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.040
And then it kept on going on and on.
So, in terms of creation…

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:16.880
it became like building brands,
building retail formats,

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:20.640
then getting into NBFC, logistic business,
insurance.

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:21.719
So, multiple things.

00:14:21.799 --> 00:14:24.200
And then, investing
into a lot of entrepreneurs.

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:27.680
Right. When was that moment
when you really scaled?

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.600
Like, when you guys became really big?

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:33.640
'Cause I remember growing up,
like, your brands were everywhere.

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:37.120
Everyone of us knew you,
you were on the cover of magazines…

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.480
Like, you were talking
about that book, no?

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:42.160
There was one book,
it was kind of like the Bible that time.

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:45.480
-To study the retail…
-I think, if you look at…

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:49.928
If I look back,
because I am in a different state of mind

00:14:50.008 --> 00:14:52.960
or in terms of business at the moment,

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:54.720
so I have done…

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:57.760
It might appear that I have done
what people do in three generations.

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:00.080
I created and I destroyed everything.

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:01.759
So, creation and destruction,

00:15:01.839 --> 00:15:05.200
and maybe if there is a chance
to create something more.

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:08.640
But… but it was a process
which was fantastic.

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:13.560
First was destroying your old thoughts,
destroying your parents' thoughts,

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:15.391
creating something out of that.

00:15:15.471 --> 00:15:18.320
And then, destroying your thoughts again
and again.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:21.280
Because we went into luxury,
and we went into masses.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:23.420
We went to the lowest end
of the population

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:27.480
with a store format called Aadhaar,
which was below 50,000 population.

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:31.600
And we dealt with the highest end
by creating something called Foodhall.

00:15:31.680 --> 00:15:35.361
And in terms of departmental stores,
Central to Brand Factory.

00:15:35.441 --> 00:15:39.520
So, we catered to a lot of audiences,
and there were a lot of learnings from…

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:41.576
Like, Hindustan Lever
at that point of time,

00:15:41.656 --> 00:15:44.800
how do you create brands
at every segment of the population?

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:49.320
So, I think branding was something
which interested us.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:53.680
Yeah, so we laddered many brands
in the retail formats.

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:59.080
And, so, it was a journey, I would say.
For 30 years, we compounded at 30%.

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:04.680
For 30 years, we did grow every year.

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:07.201
And, uh, so…

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:10.016
But now it's a different journey.
So, another experience,

00:16:10.096 --> 00:16:12.360
I have become more philosophical
than doing…

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:15.320
Right. It's an incredible journey.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:18.680
And out of all the things
you could have done, like, why…

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:21.480
Big Bazaar and Future Group?

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:24.840
Like, why… How did you arrive at,
"This is the thing, this is my calling"?

00:16:24.920 --> 00:16:27.400
Was it just the weaving thing
which led to this?

00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:31.400
Uh, before creating Big Bazaar,
I had a format in mind

00:16:31.480 --> 00:16:34.520
that we'll create a marketplace
for brands.

00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:38.240
So, Central was originally conceptualized
much before Big Bazaar for me.

00:16:39.120 --> 00:16:41.480
But then, Big Bazaar came about…

00:16:41.560 --> 00:16:44.200
I started visiting the bazaars
and the haats

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.160
which used to happen in small towns.

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:49.480
So, people used to take the markets.

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:51.480
So, we thought,
"Why can't we create markets

00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:53.960
"with that hustle and bustle in a city?"

00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:57.320
I had not seen Walmart then.
I had not seen any other retail format.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:16:59.640
So, we thought, "Let's try this."

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:02.960
And so, then, the idea was to build scale.

00:17:03.040 --> 00:17:05.400
So we opened three stores in 22 days

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:07.880
so that we could build some volumes
and some scale.

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:09.320
So it was a market, hustle-bustle,

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:11.840
we thought that should be
a butt-brush effect.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:15.400
People should meet each other,
people should… There should be a crowd.

00:17:15.481 --> 00:17:17.640
Because crowd can only get crowd.

00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:20.080
So, it was different experience then.

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:23.240
But we must say that, sir,
in this country,

00:17:23.320 --> 00:17:27.200
somebody who has thought of organizing
retail and started at that scale,

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:31.560
and people started believing
because your format started working.

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:35.360
I think several format will come,
get destroyed, will come again,

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:36.923
futuristic and all,

00:17:37.003 --> 00:17:40.720
but you have given
that genesis that retail can be organized.

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:43.600
[Nikhil] Like, the kids say today, like,
he's like the OG of commerce.

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:47.280
-I call him Father of Organizing Retail.
-[Nikhil] Original gangster. [chuckles]

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:49.340
-[Vidit] Yeah, yeah. 100%.
-I think…

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:52.320
We have learned so much,
directly, indirectly.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:54.508 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:56.960
Somebody becomes a catalyst to do that.
So I think we got a…

00:17:57.040 --> 00:17:58.800
You have.
You have done that for retail, for sure.

00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:01.440
We got that opportunity to do it.

00:18:01.520 --> 00:18:04.280
And I think once you start looking at it
from a consumer lens,

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:07.160
you can create something much, much more.

00:18:07.240 --> 00:18:09.400
Because you are looking at the consumer
and creating something,

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:11.880
not looking at yourself
and creating something.

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:14.400
So, we created
that consumer understanding,

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:15.800
trying to… We…

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:19.480
As a group, we have an organization
which is called Futurebrands

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:24.280
wherein we, from the last 15 years,
every six months, we do a Bharat Darshan.

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:27.920
And we record every societal change
happening in the country.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.440
We record every lyrics written
in the country,

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:33.440
anything which becomes popular,
we make it a point…

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.440
So, like, when we used to get huge crowds
in Big Bazaar stores,

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:40.360
we went to Tirupati temple
to understand how to manage crowds.

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:41.880
[rambunctious laughter]

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:44.160
So, India is a fascinating country,
in a way.

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:47.040
-"Release this box."
-And what did you learn from Tirupati?

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:48.280
Tirupati, unbelievable management.

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:51.640 line:1%
Crazy. How to manage crowds was something…

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:53.120 line:1%
How do you create that…

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:55.760 line:1%
[speaks in Hindi]

00:18:55.840 --> 00:18:57.400
…make people stand in the queue,

00:18:57.480 --> 00:19:00.080
give them water, give them everything,
make them patient.

00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:03.440
And you learn from everywhere.
Everywhere.

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:06.440
India has all the experiences
which you can experience and learn from.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:09.000
-[Vidit] Wow!
-Mm.

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:10.840
Turning Tirupati to retail, huh?

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:13.520
That should have been
the title of the book.

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:14.947
My first retail store experience

00:19:15.027 --> 00:19:17.240
where we got inspired
was Saravana stores in Chennai.

00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:19.520
Where they sell idli and all?

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:21.360
Everything they used sell
in one single place.

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.680
-Saravana Bhavan, right?
-Saravana Stores.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:24.960
[Sujeet] Stores, stores.

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:28.240
They used to sell
utensils the most, fabric…

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:31.880
-Oh, I was thinking of Saravana Bhavan…
-Saravana Bhavan is… that is the food…

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:33.600
That's a food thing,
but the store is huge.

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:34.960
Huge.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:38.200
-Appliances, everything they sell.
-[Kishore] Yeah, everything.

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:40.151
So, Big Bazaar was, in fact,
conceptualized

00:19:40.231 --> 00:19:42.880
from inspiration of Saravana,
more than anything else.

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:46.360 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:48.200
Yeah, like everybody here.

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:52.680
So, I have to preface this for context.
Me and Sujeet hang out a lot, all right?

00:19:52.760 --> 00:19:57.080
Like, we were together yesterday,
we travel together.

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:00.120
Uh, if he was not married…

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:02.040
[coy laughter]

00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:06.360
…people would have the wrong idea
but we end up spending…

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:09.600
I think we travel at least once
in two-three months somewhere together?

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.800
-Yes, I think last one year, yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:12.960
[Kishore] Great.

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:15.080
So I know him very well.

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:18.840
Yeah, but, let me say where I come from.

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:20.320
-[Nikhil] Yeah.
-Like Vidit was saying,

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:21.520
"I am from Meerut."

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:24.000 line:1%
So I come from a place called
Bhabua in Bihar.

00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:26.920 line:1%
It's a very small town.
I have grown up there,

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:31.240 line:1%
studied there till 12th in Hindi medium,
from Bihar Board.

00:20:31.320 --> 00:20:32.560
[Sujeet snickers]

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:39.240
And I don't know how I have gone to IIT.
Because I came to know about IIT only in…

00:20:39.320 --> 00:20:41.760
People call it "12th",
we call it "intermediate".

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:42.880
Yeah.

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:45.040
So, it was a part of college at that time.

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:47.520
When after 10th, you go to college,

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:51.840
and it's not 10+2,
it's Intermediate, then BA/BSc, whatever.

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:57.360
So I have, from Hindi medium,
converted to English, just for exam.

00:20:57.440 --> 00:21:00.440
Uh, somehow landed in IIT-Delhi.

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:04.720
I never planned to go to IIT-Delhi,
I wanted to be in IT-BHU.

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:07.680 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:14.160 line:1%
[laughing]

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:16.400 line:1%
Something happened. Uh…

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:20.400 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:22.320
I landed in Delhi. Uh…

00:21:23.320 --> 00:21:26.520
And that was my first big city,

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:28.680
and I was exposed to, like…

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:30.480 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:40.400
-[chuckles] So…
-[Nikhil] What was it? Please repeat it.

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:43.480 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:45.440
In Hindi, it's "uch vidyalaya".

00:21:45.520 --> 00:21:49.040
Uh, so… landed in IIT.

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:53.840
[chuckles]

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:55.640
[Vidit] The same thing
happened to me also.

00:21:55.720 --> 00:21:59.280
There were so many things I never saw.

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:03.400
Like, I had a smaller school, I would say,
until 12th, and when I came…

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:06.040
I have no idea, right?

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:07.120
You have all kinds of sports,

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:09.640
you have all kinds of extra curriculars
to do.

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:14.240
So, you get exposed to this right
after college… uh, right after school,

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:16.880
people go crazy. So I can totally connect
with this feeling.

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:20.280
In India, people play cricket, badminton…

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:21.960 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:22:24.361 --> 00:22:27.600
-[all laugh]
-And you will not believe,

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:31.120
even billiards and all,
I was spending so much of time,

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:33.680
by second or third year,
I was in the team.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:38.600
[chuckles] So I was playing billiards,
pool, like I said…

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:40.520
-[Nikhil] Still got good marks in IIT?
-No.

00:22:40.600 --> 00:22:43.360
[all laugh loudly]

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:47.360 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:52.520
But at that time, Y2K,
when we were passing in 2003,

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:58.440
all of 2001, 2002,
the whole job scenario was so bad…

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:00.240 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:07.920
Otherwise, people go out,
all the MNCs come to campus,

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.378
they take those first, like,
electricals, computer,

00:23:11.458 --> 00:23:13.400
all these, and then rank-wise.

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:19.800
And even if you are last from the bottom,
you'll get some job.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.560 line:1%
And it was a kind of…

00:23:25.560 --> 00:23:29.800 line:1%
And then I had, somewhere I thought…

00:23:29.880 --> 00:23:31.960 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:23:32.040 --> 00:23:33.640 line:1%
And I remember that…

00:23:33.720 --> 00:23:35.680 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:49.680
…you have to take some optional subject.

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:52.320
Like history, public ad, geography,

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:56.800
you have to study all that
general knowledge.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:59.200
And then you have to do a core subject
like physics, math,

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:01.320
as a science boy, you can choose one.

00:24:01.400 --> 00:24:03.120
Otherwise, you can choose any subject.

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:05.840 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:07.960 line:1%
Then I spent almost six months there…

00:24:12.760 --> 00:24:18.040
Somehow I decided to join some small firm…

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:19.480
where I can learn.

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:24.040
Some of my friends
connected me to some person.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:27.560
He had agreed to take me as a co-founder,
at that time, KPO.

00:24:27.640 --> 00:24:30.840
In 2000, I'm talking about 2004, 2005.

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:34.560
So, we have started a KPO.
Taking project, delivering the project,

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:37.080
we were like 25-26 people.

00:24:37.161 --> 00:24:39.800
And doing that for almost, like…

00:24:41.001 --> 00:24:44.880
And in 2008, recession came,
no project, no money.

00:24:44.960 --> 00:24:46.040
[Sujeet chuckling]

00:24:46.120 --> 00:24:49.440
And Sachin, in 2007…

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:52.840
He was one year my junior in IIT,
we were in the same hostel.

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:55.880 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:01.160 line:1%
[Sujeet and Vidit laugh]

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:05.960
I was in love with Delhi.

00:25:07.840 --> 00:25:09.880
I was settled there. Um…

00:25:11.560 --> 00:25:16.280
Then he… I think he got married early,
in 2008, he called me for his marriage.

00:25:16.360 --> 00:25:19.480 line:1%
And then… We decided to close KPO…

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:21.680 line:1%
[in Hindi] as we had no project, no money.

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:24.081
His wife is still your dentist, no?

00:25:24.161 --> 00:25:25.360
Yes.

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:27.560 line:1%
So, uh…

00:25:27.640 --> 00:25:29.800 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:46.640
Then I came in 2008. Um…

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:50.280
I was not able to imagine that…

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:52.560
Because he was…

00:26:04.040 --> 00:26:06.360 line:1%
Because Binny was two years junior to me.

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:08.034
[in Hindi] I said,
"I'll come and check it out

00:26:08.114 --> 00:26:10.160
"and then let you know
if I want to go ahead with it or not."

00:26:14.320 --> 00:26:16.680
Because all the suppliers of books
at that time were in Delhi.

