00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:47.360
what are the first five brands
that come to your mind,

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:49.960
and why do you think
there are so few brands?

00:39:50.040 --> 00:39:52.040 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:00.234
We were able to build
four-five 1,000 crore brands.

00:40:00.320 --> 00:40:04.404
Now you look at boAt in personal wear.

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:07.200
I am looking at…

00:40:07.280 --> 00:40:10.320 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:14.480
Even Mamaearth has scaled
to a certain level.

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:17.280
Not 1,000 crores,
but they are getting there.

00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:20.760
So, new-age brands are happening,
but old-age brands, Lever, Nestle,

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:23.090
they're all…
they have all built brands, yeah?

00:40:23.174 --> 00:40:25.360
-Look at the brand Maggi has built, no?
-[Sujeet] Yeah, yeah.

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:28.440
It's crazy, one single category,
one single product…

00:40:28.520 --> 00:40:29.800
-A billion dollar brand…
-But they're all…

00:40:29.880 --> 00:40:32.752
The ones which have really scaled
have been the foreign brands

00:40:32.832 --> 00:40:34.060
which have come into India.

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:37.760
I think Marico has done well, ITC,

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:42.080
I would rate it as an Indian company,
they are building a lot of brands.

00:40:42.160 --> 00:40:46.440
Britannia, in a way, they are
making a lot of Indian brands.

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:50.480 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:56.160
Amul. Amul I think is the biggest brand
India has created ever.

00:40:56.240 --> 00:40:57.860
I think for this conversation,

00:40:57.940 --> 00:41:00.501
let's not focus or fixate
upon e-commerce alone,

00:41:00.581 --> 00:41:03.440
but commerce at large, because we have…

00:41:03.520 --> 00:41:06.000
But digital commerce
is a very interesting subject.

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:08.240
And ultimately, digital….

00:41:08.302 --> 00:41:10.520
To buy anything,
it'll be a digital use in…

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:13.680
Whether it will influence you,
whether you have seen the brand digitally.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:15.600 line:1%
-So, digital is a part of your life now.
-[Sujeet] That's true.

00:41:15.680 --> 00:41:17.240 line:1%
[speaks in Hindi]

00:41:17.320 --> 00:41:19.000
You think that's the future
and physical is gonna die?

00:41:19.063 --> 00:41:21.357
-It's not about physical or digital.
-[Sujeet] I think digital…

00:41:21.441 --> 00:41:23.600 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:27.640
Yes, after seeing a photo on Instagram,

00:41:27.720 --> 00:41:29.198
you decide what to buy
in that local market.

00:41:29.282 --> 00:41:30.800
It is a part of your life now.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:33.440
I don't see them as two separate things.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:35.560
Hmm. So you think…

00:41:36.747 --> 00:41:39.480 line:1%
in the future,
for these consumer-facing brands,

00:41:39.560 --> 00:41:40.960 line:1%
let's say for example…

00:41:41.043 --> 00:41:43.400 line:1%
…the four or five brands
that you were talking about…

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:47.895
What is the split right now of people
buying them online

00:41:47.975 --> 00:41:49.400
and what is the split offline?

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:51.800
Firstly, I am not building,
my daughters are doing it.

00:41:51.880 --> 00:41:53.431
I am maybe a mentor, they are…

00:41:53.513 --> 00:41:57.120
Because I don't belong to that generation
who think digitally.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:01.960
The last thing we did digitally
was to build a whole thing around data.

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:03.040 line:1%
[speaks in Hindi]

00:42:03.120 --> 00:42:05.000 line:1%
We did Big Bazaar to our delivery,

00:42:05.080 --> 00:42:07.720
which became very successful,
we got a break.

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:12.840
We started FutureBazaar.com
when Flipkart had… along the same time.

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:15.786
[Sujeet] I think a little bit delayed,
but, yeah, around the same. 2008.

00:42:15.869 --> 00:42:18.800
Around the same time, 2008-09. Yeah.

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:20.833
So we attempted digital…

00:42:20.916 --> 00:42:23.600
Being physical, attempting digital
was the biggest mistake,

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:26.840
because you can't think …
People who are born digital think digital.

00:42:28.160 --> 00:42:30.760
We were born physical and thinking digital
was adding one more layer.

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:31.840
That doesn't work.

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:34.680
[Nikhil] And what do you think the recipe
is now? What could work?

00:42:34.760 --> 00:42:36.240
You have to think digital now.

00:42:36.320 --> 00:42:38.560
But also have a physical presence?

00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:41.960
Physical… You sell through every medium.
But you have to think digital.

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:44.901
Everything… When we used
to build brands earlier,

00:42:44.981 --> 00:42:46.960
it was newspaper advertising,
television advertising…

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:48.080 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:42:48.160 --> 00:42:50.707
Now you can't build a brand
on newspaper advertising

00:42:50.787 --> 00:42:52.040
or television advertising.

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:53.400 line:1%
Or outdoor.

00:42:56.452 --> 00:43:00.280
Yes, digital marketing, targeting digital…

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:02.000
So you have to think digital,
the consumers are different…

00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:04.800 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:09.440
Even before we talk about e-commerce
or digitally buying something…

00:43:10.400 --> 00:43:14.360
why do you think,
from a very psychological standpoint,

00:43:14.440 --> 00:43:18.120
why do you think somebody buys a product?

00:43:18.200 --> 00:43:22.240
What in their psyche instigates them
to buy a certain product?

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:24.760
Why do some products do better
than other products?

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:27.691
And do you think…

00:43:27.775 --> 00:43:31.400
See, I'm not talking about
the essentials that we all need,

00:43:31.480 --> 00:43:32.760
but I'm talking about shopping,

00:43:32.821 --> 00:43:36.680
shopping in the sense of the word
that we know it today…

00:43:36.760 --> 00:43:40.120
Do you think the power dynamic in a way
shifts from

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:43.749
the seller of the product to the buy…
from the seller…

00:43:43.832 --> 00:43:46.640
from the buyer to the seller
each time somebody buys a product?

00:43:46.720 --> 00:43:49.755
Like why does somebody buy a product,
and why does a product work?

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:52.883
So, I'll tell you at least
what we see now, right?

00:43:52.967 --> 00:43:57.560
Like, now, because of social,
there's massive FOMO in the world.

00:43:57.640 --> 00:43:58.640
Right? So there's…

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:00.960
People call it inspiration,
but a lot of this is FOMO.

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:03.000
Right? Like, no one wants to be left out.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:08.240
We see lots and lots of shopping
gets inspired by social media.

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:10.720
Right? Like, by Instagram,
by this and that.

00:44:10.800 --> 00:44:14.720
One of the very common products
that people use on the Meesho app,

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:19.320
is people take photograph, and they search
that same photograph and buy.

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:21.440
And most of those photographs
come from Instagram.

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:25.720
So how big is social media
as an influencer

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:27.280
part of Meesho's overall sales?

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:29.711
I would say it's very hard to attribute,
because in many cases people come and…

00:44:29.795 --> 00:44:31.240
Both direct and indirect?

00:44:31.320 --> 00:44:33.880
It's a lot. Even the way we design,

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:36.520
what kind of trends are coming up,
what kind of things you see,

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:40.920
everything is driven a lot by what data
we see on social. It's a big part.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.480
So, I'm saying
direct attribution we can see

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:45.640
when people are really searching
that image, and it's an Instagram image.

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:47.920
So, that we know, and that's a large part.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:52.200
But even otherwise, we see everyone
deciding what to buy and what not to buy

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:53.640
driven a lot from social media.

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:56.760
So you're saying there is this
one central body, in a way,

00:44:56.840 --> 00:45:00.240
of influential people
who decides what is cool,

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:03.520
and then everybody decides
they need that product in their life?

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:05.920
To some extent, yes. Right?
Like, that's happening.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:08.064
Now people are seeing
a lot of celebrities,

00:45:08.144 --> 00:45:10.600
now they are also seeing
these influencers come up.

00:45:10.680 --> 00:45:14.480
And how high does that chain go?
Let's say we look at an influencer,

00:45:14.560 --> 00:45:18.920
who does the influencer look at?
Who, in turn, does that person look at?

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.560
Is it a corporation
which is setting trends that are cool,

00:45:22.640 --> 00:45:25.040
or is it organically evolving from people?

00:45:25.920 --> 00:45:28.120
So, at least from what we see now,

00:45:28.200 --> 00:45:31.080
it may have started
with being very concentrated,

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:34.026
but now, even, like I see,
like BlissClub starting, right?

00:45:34.109 --> 00:45:35.840
Like, they leverage influencers
quite a lot.

00:45:35.903 --> 00:45:38.240
That entire brand was, by the way,
built on Instagram.

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:40.360
Like, everything was built on Instagram.

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:41.513
And they found people.

00:45:41.593 --> 00:45:44.286
So, now, there are influencers
that people can relate with.

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:46.080
"Hey, this influencer looks like me,

00:45:46.163 --> 00:45:48.000
"wears the kinds of things I like,
and I follow that person."

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:49.520
And some of the influencers,

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:51.568
very original kind of products
they choose,

00:45:51.651 --> 00:45:53.080
and they recommend, and so on.

00:45:53.160 --> 00:45:55.256
So it's not very concentrated that,

00:45:55.339 --> 00:45:57.633
"Hey, this person looks at this,
and that person looks at this."

00:45:57.717 --> 00:46:00.640
I feel now it's very decentralized
to some extent,

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:03.480
and everyone knows what kind of person

00:46:03.556 --> 00:46:05.182
feels like a body double to me, right?

00:46:05.266 --> 00:46:07.244
Like, "Hey, this person
has the same beliefs,

00:46:07.324 --> 00:46:08.720
"same likings, same kind of body,

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:12.360
"and I like this person.
I wanna buy what they look good in."

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:13.880
So I feel that's happening…

00:46:13.941 --> 00:46:16.402
Do you think at the very core
of this distinction,

00:46:16.485 --> 00:46:20.322
you're saying people are mandating,

00:46:20.406 --> 00:46:24.201
or people are governing what becomes cool,
and it's not the brands or corporations?

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:25.280
Correct.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:26.680
People are leading
and brands are following?

00:46:26.760 --> 00:46:29.280
To some extent, now I see this
to be very strong.

00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:31.917
And I feel this is only getting
bigger and bigger.

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:35.800
No, but there is a reason for it.
Like he was saying,

00:46:35.880 --> 00:46:40.280
social media, especially
these video platforms,

00:46:40.342 --> 00:46:42.800
let's say TikTok, Josh, whatever.

00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:46.560
Instagram, Facebook, there are
so many distributions, big platforms

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:50.480
where more than hundreds
of millions of users…

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:54.600 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:02.072
And they like those videos.

00:47:02.156 --> 00:47:05.660
It's very hard for us to relate
to why these guys are watching so much.

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:11.560
And ultimately, some style, some product,
something, they pick.

00:47:11.640 --> 00:47:15.120
And they want to look like it
because they spent so much of time.

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:19.240
So I think, like he was saying that
social, I think it is becoming mainstream.

00:47:20.760 --> 00:47:25.262
I was just telling you,
when we were solving this predictability,

00:47:25.346 --> 00:47:30.000
"Hey, the goods will be delivered
within one day, two days or one week,"

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:32.600
depending on the location and all,

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:35.189
I think this generation,
for them, it's a given.

00:47:36.080 --> 00:47:38.880
They are not thinking about, "Hey, how…"

00:47:38.942 --> 00:47:42.080
I was talking about
payment gateway integration…

00:47:42.160 --> 00:47:44.800 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:47:47.880 --> 00:47:52.720
Uh, I think people now want to look good,

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:54.960
want to look different.

00:47:55.040 --> 00:47:56.877
If you are asking who are the influencers?

00:47:56.960 --> 00:48:02.400
If, in their society, they know some guys
who have 1,000 followers,

00:48:02.480 --> 00:48:03.880
10,000 followers,

00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:07.320
and they are getting inspired, thinking,
"I can become an influencer."

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:11.600
They are endorsing the brand.
Local brands, chips, some shop, something.

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:13.200
And they are innovative.

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:16.045
Because they want to look different
in every video

00:48:16.125 --> 00:48:18.160
because they are creating reels also.

00:48:18.240 --> 00:48:20.920
So what do they do? They go to malls,

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:24.280
go to changing rooms,
just change and take one video…

00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:27.080
Because they cannot spend that much money.

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:30.160
See, I think now they endorse
in a different way.

00:48:30.800 --> 00:48:34.040
So, is that the future
instead of marketing on newspaper, TV…

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:39.160
I think, the way we look at it,
people being a part of the old economy,

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:43.006
we believe that whenever a dominant media
or communication method changes,

00:48:43.090 --> 00:48:45.175
everything changes around it.

00:48:45.240 --> 00:48:49.200
So when there was a newspaper,
then the radio, then the television…

00:48:49.263 --> 00:48:51.800
Television commoditized, built brands.

00:48:51.880 --> 00:48:55.000
Now that's social media
and social interaction.

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:59.280
I think mobile phone
makes you very individualistic.

00:48:59.360 --> 00:49:02.800
Because now at every home,
everybody has a different breakfast,

00:49:02.860 --> 00:49:04.800
everybody has a different meal.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:08.720
Earlier, the family used to sit together
and had one kind of meal.

00:49:08.800 --> 00:49:11.409
Things have changed,
and we have become very individualistic

00:49:11.489 --> 00:49:13.200
because everybody has a personal phone.

00:49:13.280 --> 00:49:15.680
So, things are changing around it.

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:18.400
So, every person has personal preferences
of an influencer.

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:22.320
You need so many people
now to get influenced.

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:26.509
Somebody will get influenced by something,
somebody will get influenced by something.

00:49:26.592 --> 00:49:27.840
Earlier, it was mass advertising.

00:49:27.920 --> 00:49:31.960
I remember we made a movie,
and there was a particular dress

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:33.360
which was made by Biba,

00:49:33.440 --> 00:49:36.602
and they still sell that dress
after 14 years or 15 years.

00:49:36.686 --> 00:49:40.940
And that… Virtually, that dress made Biba
as a brand also to a great extent.

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:42.760
Earlier, there were other influences,

00:49:42.840 --> 00:49:45.986
but it was commoditized
to a great, great extent.

00:49:46.080 --> 00:49:50.120
But today, things are different.
It's getting individualistic. More…

00:49:50.200 --> 00:49:52.800
And then, you have to find
that kind of users together,

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:54.600
and make them into a group.

00:49:54.680 --> 00:49:56.789
So, for the future of building a product,

00:49:56.873 --> 00:49:59.840
for the new consumer brands
that are coming up today,

00:49:59.920 --> 00:50:02.400
is the go-to strategy just that?

00:50:02.461 --> 00:50:04.560
Paying influencers
to promote your product?

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:06.040
No, no, I think it's a…

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:10.093
For brands, I think now,
it's a very core part.

00:50:10.177 --> 00:50:11.721
Like, if you don't align
with the influencers…

00:50:11.804 --> 00:50:13.320
Like, say the brand
could also have a message.

00:50:13.400 --> 00:50:15.400
Like I could be saying,

00:50:15.480 --> 00:50:18.047
"My brand is sustainable."
"My brand is XYZ."

00:50:18.127 --> 00:50:20.520
"My brand does a certain kind of fashion."

00:50:21.480 --> 00:50:24.520
Does the brand
try to build their distinction

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:26.640
through that brand message,

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:29.640
or is the lower hanging fruit

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:33.712
going to the influencers who have
the widest reach and paying them money

00:50:33.792 --> 00:50:35.320
to adopt the brand in a way?

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:37.600
It's happening a lot.

00:50:37.680 --> 00:50:40.120
And, by the way, it's just not about
finding the biggest influencer.

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:43.480
As I was saying, now influencers stand
for different things.

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:47.097
So, you have to find someone
who is very close to the philosophy

00:50:47.177 --> 00:50:48.840
that the brand wants to build.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:51.480
So, an influencer is an intermediary
between a brand and the customer?

00:50:51.560 --> 00:50:54.040
Yeah, yeah, yeah. By the way,
people have become very conscious.

00:50:54.120 --> 00:50:56.071
They look at everything.
"Hey, who have you picked?

00:50:56.151 --> 00:50:57.400
"What does this person believe in?

00:50:57.480 --> 00:51:00.600
"You say sustainable, I see this person
using a plastic water bottle."

00:51:00.680 --> 00:51:02.600
"I don't believe this person
is sustainable."

00:51:02.680 --> 00:51:05.400
My point is that everything,
every detail somehow matters now.

00:51:05.480 --> 00:51:07.160
-[Nikhil] Right.
-Because people spend so much time.

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:10.120
So, it's just not… You can't go…

00:51:10.200 --> 00:51:11.360
And that's why influencers work.

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:14.040
And very, very small influencers
are very effective,

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:18.320
because it's just not going to
the celebrity with millions of followers.

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:21.960
You have to find someone who connects
with the principle of the brand.

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:24.800
[Sujeet] If you'll see, I think…

00:51:24.880 --> 00:51:28.280
Earlier, like he was saying,
the unidimensional controlled channel.

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:31.560
Let's say newspapers, TV,
and we were controlled.

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:34.228
Because of the social media revolution,

00:51:34.308 --> 00:51:38.800
multiple access innovations are happening,
multiple access.

00:51:38.880 --> 00:51:40.920
And it's very hard to pick one trend.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.921
Some trends are working
in tier 1, some tier 2,

00:51:44.001 --> 00:51:46.040
some in the high-paying capacity,

00:51:46.120 --> 00:51:49.400
some Gen Z, some, uh-uh-uh, millennials.

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:53.800
And it's very hard to pick trends.
But if you'll see,

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:58.400
the platforms which are responsible
for social media,

00:51:58.480 --> 00:52:00.280
let's say Instagram or Facebook…

00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:02.800
Now they are creating a fund.

00:52:02.881 --> 00:52:07.680
So, to engage these influencers…
Because if commercially they will not…

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:11.040
Commercially, if they will not be engaged,

00:52:11.120 --> 00:52:14.600
it's very hard for them
to come again and innovate.

00:52:14.680 --> 00:52:16.968
So, now they are creating a fund for it.

00:52:17.048 --> 00:52:19.534
And, somehow,
they are creating an economics…

00:52:19.614 --> 00:52:21.160
Currently, those are broken.

00:52:21.240 --> 00:52:25.680
Because the people who are finding
those number of influencers,

00:52:25.760 --> 00:52:28.560
they are creating that infrastructure,
but currently, it's broken.

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:31.760
So, big innovations are happening,
how to create that fund

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:34.104
so that all these influencers
at multiple access

00:52:34.184 --> 00:52:35.680
keep engaging with the platform.

00:52:36.521 --> 00:52:41.041
So, I think… And I see retail
as becoming a by-product of that.

00:52:41.120 --> 00:52:44.137
And do you think celebrities…
Like, I'm talking about

00:52:44.217 --> 00:52:47.920
old-school celebrities,
Bollywood, cricketers…

00:52:49.161 --> 00:52:52.440
do you think that connection
has somewhere gotten lost

00:52:52.520 --> 00:52:54.920
because people have assumed

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.720
in their minds
that they are for sale, in a way,

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:02.400
and rarely ever do they believe
in the product they are selling,

00:53:02.461 --> 00:53:05.924
and will the trend in the future be
that brands do not go

00:53:06.004 --> 00:53:10.371
to Bollywood or cricket, but they go
to more micro-influencers, in a way,

00:53:10.451 --> 00:53:11.800
who are more authentic?

00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:13.280
I think…

00:53:14.482 --> 00:53:16.400
it is happening slightly,

00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:18.480
but I think that's still
not the prominent reason.

00:53:18.560 --> 00:53:20.281
Like, the reason people go
to influencers…

00:53:20.361 --> 00:53:21.960
Because earlier, by the way,
it was binary.

00:53:22.040 --> 00:53:23.280
Either you have a big celebrity
or you don't.

00:53:23.360 --> 00:53:24.360
[Nikhil] Right.

00:53:24.440 --> 00:53:27.840
And until you become large enough
to afford a celebrity, you can't do it.

00:53:27.920 --> 00:53:30.560
Now, people can start on day one.
You could be a very small one,

00:53:30.640 --> 00:53:32.480
you find a small influencer
who connects with your philosophy,

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:34.560
and people keep graduating.

00:53:34.640 --> 00:53:36.149
There are still very few influencers

00:53:36.229 --> 00:53:38.040
who have the same following
as celebrities,

00:53:38.120 --> 00:53:39.840
so what you're saying
still hasn't happened.

00:53:39.920 --> 00:53:42.120
But I believe that'll happen soon.

00:53:42.200 --> 00:53:43.280
In the next few years,

00:53:43.360 --> 00:53:45.360
some large celebrities
will have the same following as…

00:53:45.440 --> 00:53:48.560
Er, some large influencers
with the same following as celebrities.

00:53:48.640 --> 00:53:49.920
You guys do a lot of marketing.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:51.440
We do. And we are seeing, by the way…

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:52.960
[Nikhil] What is your marketing budget
per year?

00:53:53.040 --> 00:53:54.400
How much did you spend last year?

00:53:54.480 --> 00:53:56.840
It's a large amount,
I won't mention the number here.

00:53:56.920 --> 00:53:59.320
-But I'm saying it does not matter.
-I want you to say it.

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:01.480
No, but I won't mention still.
[chuckles coyly]

00:54:01.560 --> 00:54:05.602
But let's say Meesho spends something like
2,000 crores a year to market…

00:54:05.682 --> 00:54:08.120
What I'm wondering is:

00:54:08.183 --> 00:54:11.943
How do you decide the allocation
of that money?

00:54:12.040 --> 00:54:15.600
What have you learnt? Say, for example,
last year, you sponsored IPL,

00:54:15.680 --> 00:54:19.440
and this and that, and stuff like that,
in actors and stuff,

00:54:19.520 --> 00:54:22.000
what have you learnt from that experience?

00:54:22.823 --> 00:54:24.560
And what will you change going forward?

00:54:25.383 --> 00:54:29.240
Yeah, so the one thing we have always seen
very effective is we are very local.

00:54:29.320 --> 00:54:30.600
We go as local as possible

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:34.080
because our audience space
is very heterogenous.

00:54:34.160 --> 00:54:37.400
Unlike tier 1 which also is like very…

00:54:37.480 --> 00:54:39.640
If you look at Instagram,
it looks very homogenous, right?

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:42.228
Like tier 1 tends to behave
very similarly.

00:54:42.308 --> 00:54:44.520
As soon as you go beyond, it does not.

00:54:44.600 --> 00:54:48.600
So we've always been very local.
So, we go to Andhra Pradesh and Telangana

00:54:48.680 --> 00:54:50.971
and pick an actor
or pick an actress or a celebrity

00:54:51.051 --> 00:54:52.400
that connects with that person.

00:54:52.480 --> 00:54:54.560
So, I'm saying we have always been
very local,

00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:56.200
and we have seen that
to be very effective,

00:54:56.280 --> 00:55:00.320
um, but at the end of the day,
it's capital allocation, right?

00:55:00.400 --> 00:55:03.280
You spend X amount or you spend Y amount,

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:05.640
-you see where the ROI happens.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

00:55:05.720 --> 00:55:07.720
We've seen, over time,

00:55:07.800 --> 00:55:11.040
like, it's not that you need to have
a celebrity all the time, right?

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:13.040
So we keep changing celebrities so that…

00:55:13.960 --> 00:55:16.337
the company's image
is not attached to one person.

00:55:16.417 --> 00:55:17.880
That is also a risk,
at the end of the day.

00:55:17.960 --> 00:55:20.040
How much does your ROI go up
when you use a celebrity?

00:55:20.120 --> 00:55:22.960
-Huh?
-How much does you ROI go up…

00:55:23.042 --> 00:55:25.522
while you're using a celebrity
versus not using?

00:55:25.602 --> 00:55:28.120
-Is there a tangible difference?
-Very hard to estimate, yeah.

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:31.920
Super hard. Like, if someone asks you
this question, it's all anecdotal.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.200
It's… Like, people build
stories around it.

00:55:34.280 --> 00:55:35.680
No one can estimate.

00:55:36.480 --> 00:55:38.080
Uh…

00:55:38.160 --> 00:55:41.000
Which was your biggest hit of marketing
last year? What worked best?

00:55:42.360 --> 00:55:44.120
[Vidit] So, our Diwali campaign
did very well,

00:55:44.200 --> 00:55:45.200
which is where we did localization.

00:55:45.280 --> 00:55:46.400
So, we kind of…

00:55:46.480 --> 00:55:49.880
We had different celebrities
for different parts of the country.

00:55:49.960 --> 00:55:53.480
Right? We had Sourav Ganguly
for West Bengal,

00:55:53.560 --> 00:55:57.360
we had Ram Charan
for a certain state in South India.

00:55:57.440 --> 00:56:00.520
So, I'm saying it's… it's…
Basically, we went very local.

00:56:00.600 --> 00:56:02.096
And we saw that to be much more effective

00:56:02.176 --> 00:56:04.160
than having one person
who appeals to all the country,

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:06.720
because we realized
it's close to impossible

00:56:06.800 --> 00:56:08.760
to find one person
who appeals to everyone.

00:56:08.840 --> 00:56:09.840
You can find cricketers,

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:11.920
but they still appeal to males
and not to females.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.880
So, it's very, very hard.
So, I'm saying we have…

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:17.440
We found localization
to be very effective.

00:56:17.520 --> 00:56:20.240
-Hmm. Should we eat off and then continue?
-[Sujeet] Yeah, yeah.

00:56:20.320 --> 00:56:21.360
You wanna say something?

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:24.240
No. I was just saying that
even celebrities,

00:56:24.320 --> 00:56:29.200
they are investing significant time
to become an influencer,

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:30.680
if you see the trend.

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:32.625 line:1%
Like a cricketer is showing,

00:56:32.705 --> 00:56:34.640 line:1%
"I'm going to bed", singing.

00:56:34.720 --> 00:56:39.080
[stuttering] Showing someone…
You'll see all those.

00:56:39.160 --> 00:56:42.320
And they are, like,
a serious of time they spend.

00:56:42.400 --> 00:56:44.480
They also understand those trends.

00:56:45.280 --> 00:56:48.720
So they want to…
Even in that space, they are competing,

00:56:48.800 --> 00:56:51.520
they want to become
one of the largest influencers.

00:56:52.662 --> 00:56:57.000
In our space, in fintech, there are some…

00:56:57.080 --> 00:57:01.520
There is Sharan, there is Rachana Ranade,
there is Think School.

00:57:01.582 --> 00:57:02.800
I think these guys are…

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:06.122
Uh, especially people like Think School,

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:08.040
uh, I think there is a…

00:57:08.920 --> 00:57:12.720
there is a big divide between
the quality of content they are doing

00:57:12.800 --> 00:57:14.200
and other people are doing.

00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:16.160
I don't know how they have
arrived at that point…

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:17.840
I'm not an investor in Think School,

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:20.520
I'm not promoting them
in anyway whatsoever.

00:57:20.600 --> 00:57:26.640
But I think the future
of information dissemination,

00:57:26.720 --> 00:57:31.480
even about finance, is going to move
from traditional channels

00:57:31.560 --> 00:57:32.582
to people like them.

00:57:33.382 --> 00:57:36.720
Like, I don't think the day is far,
five years from now,

00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:40.080
somebody will not be watching the news,
they will be watching Think School…

00:57:40.160 --> 00:57:41.360
for their news.

00:57:42.601 --> 00:57:45.520
And I wonder how
this entire equation changes,

00:57:45.600 --> 00:57:48.960
and who becomes celebrities
of ten years from now.

00:57:49.920 --> 00:57:52.920
It'd be quite interesting
to see how the world changes, though.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:55.320
I think celebrity…

00:57:55.401 --> 00:57:57.280
I think earlier because…

00:57:57.360 --> 00:58:00.440
Most of the followers,
they're related to celebrities.

00:58:00.520 --> 00:58:03.000
I think in my mind, let's say,
if I like cricket,

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:04.560
or let's say some sport,

00:58:04.640 --> 00:58:07.880
it's a skill game,
I think that will not change.

00:58:07.960 --> 00:58:09.960
I am still going to prefer that.

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:15.320
But how commercially I can associate?
I think that might be different.

00:58:15.400 --> 00:58:18.000
But lots of things that I liked
was because that guy was doing it.

00:58:18.080 --> 00:58:22.360
I wanted to be seen like him
or something like fitness or…

00:58:22.440 --> 00:58:25.080
or some of the clothing styles.

00:58:25.160 --> 00:58:28.040
But who will sell those products…
might be different.

00:58:28.120 --> 00:58:32.800
I think like we were speaking,
let's get some insights from sir.

00:58:32.880 --> 00:58:37.000
We want to know the past, the present,
and the future of commerce in the country.

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:38.760
[in Hindi] No one can explain it
better than you.

00:58:38.840 --> 00:58:40.280
[Sujeet] You have seen it all.

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:45.840
I think, uh, whatever 30-35 years
we've worked,

00:58:45.935 --> 00:58:48.920
there are a lot of things
which you learn during the journey.

00:58:48.996 --> 00:58:51.120
And journey is,

00:58:51.200 --> 00:58:53.240
a lot of people believe
India is an infinite market

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:55.476
because of 20% of the world's population.

00:58:56.476 --> 00:59:00.040
And I think that's…
India is a very, very interesting country,

00:59:00.120 --> 00:59:03.080
the most heterogenous country
you can ever believe in.

00:59:03.160 --> 00:59:07.520
I will give you an interesting example
of a temple or a religious economy.

00:59:07.600 --> 00:59:11.040 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:59:13.080 --> 00:59:15.120 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

00:59:30.480 --> 00:59:32.936
And I believe 20% of India
or 30% of India,

00:59:33.016 --> 00:59:35.240
in some sense, lives on government aid.

00:59:43.960 --> 00:59:48.200
But unfortunately, the reports
which the consulting companies make…

00:59:48.280 --> 00:59:50.200
I was just reading all the data…

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:51.347 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:03.518
And to make that happen…

01:00:03.598 --> 01:00:05.080
It can't happen with commodity play

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:09.720
or it can't happen with…
where the value addition is not there.

01:00:09.800 --> 01:00:13.360
So, my theory which… I wrote it also
a long time back in my book

01:00:13.440 --> 01:00:17.200
is anybody… I call that
India is divided into three parts.

01:00:17.280 --> 01:00:20.400
"Three India", according to consumption:
India 1, India 2, India 3.

01:00:20.480 --> 01:00:22.400
India 1 is the consuming class.

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:25.760
Anybody who has a domestic help
for me is a consuming class.

01:00:25.840 --> 01:00:28.595
Because consuming
does not mean basic consumption,

01:00:28.675 --> 01:00:30.480
but some value added consumption.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:33.120
India 2 is a serving class
which makes our lives better.

01:00:33.200 --> 01:00:36.280
The driver, the helpers, the peon,
the watchman, the liftman.

01:00:36.360 --> 01:00:39.320
And for every one India 1,
there is 3-3.5 India 2.

01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:42.680
And unfortunately, India 1 doesn't give
enough money to India 2

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:46.760
to make them consume
discretionary products.

01:00:47.920 --> 01:00:51.600
And then, there is India 3,
which is farm laborers,

01:00:51.680 --> 01:00:54.800
daily aides, factory workers.

01:00:54.880 --> 01:00:56.680 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:02.720 line:1%
And that's not huge.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:07.960
I would say, in a city like Bombay,
it's a very interesting definition.

01:01:08.040 --> 01:01:09.960
Until some years ago…

01:01:11.320 --> 01:01:13.760
25% of people used to live in apartments.

01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:16.840
I would say ten years ago.
Today, it might be 35%.

01:01:17.640 --> 01:01:20.400
5%-8% people lived in chawls.

01:01:20.480 --> 01:01:22.480
And the balance lived in slums.

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:25.280
So…

01:01:27.680 --> 01:01:31.080
India, I think every city will represent
in some way or the other…

01:01:31.160 --> 01:01:33.120
But if you had to aggregate the country,
what do you think?

01:01:33.200 --> 01:01:36.200
I would say 11%-13% would be
the consuming class.

01:01:36.280 --> 01:01:37.960
-India 1?
-India 1.

01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:39.600
[Vidit] Which is 20 crore.

01:01:39.680 --> 01:01:42.080
Which is around 20 crores.
[clearing throat]

01:01:42.920 --> 01:01:45.480
And it might be growing.
And I think it's growing.

01:01:46.680 --> 01:01:50.840
And at what pace of growth will depend…
will determine everything.

01:01:50.920 --> 01:01:54.400
And unfortunately, we live
in that community only. That India 1.

01:01:54.480 --> 01:01:56.400 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:02:07.280 --> 01:02:09.520 line:1%
[all laugh]

01:02:12.240 --> 01:02:13.920
"I wanted to see India."

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:15.760 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:22.440
And that's why I always say…

01:02:22.520 --> 01:02:25.320
There was a movie which became
very popular during our times.

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:27.360 line:1%
There was a movie called
Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro.

01:02:27.440 --> 01:02:30.440 line:1%
There was a song called
"Hum Honge Kamyab Ek Din".

01:02:30.520 --> 01:02:32.900 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:02:32.980 --> 01:02:35.280 line:1%
In India, we want to succeed.

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:39.880
But I think India is 20%…
18%-20% of the world's population.

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:43.200
For the whole world, I think it was
the European economy,

01:02:43.280 --> 01:02:46.080
the American economy which consumes,
which made the world grow.

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:48.040
Then the Chinese economy
which made the world grow.

01:02:48.120 --> 01:02:49.120
Now, it's India's time.

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:53.800
India will have to learn to consume much,
much more than what they are consuming.

01:02:53.880 --> 01:02:56.960
And that's what will drive
economic growth.

01:02:57.040 --> 01:03:00.000
[Sujeet] But some of the numbers,
if you will see, sir…

01:03:00.080 --> 01:03:04.981
I'm not contesting about A, B, and C,
they are a bucket.

01:03:05.061 --> 01:03:08.080
The places we have come
from, I totally agree.

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:11.000
But some of the numbers if you'll see,
if it's true,

01:03:11.080 --> 01:03:13.142
I think it's mind-boggling.

01:03:14.120 --> 01:03:17.720
India's GDP, when I was
passing out in 2003,

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:20.160
was around $500 billion.

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:22.400
Am I right? It's been 20 years…

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:26.520
And now it's… I'm just saying
about the number published,

01:03:26.600 --> 01:03:30.600
it's around $3.5 trillion. Seven times,

01:03:30.680 --> 01:03:32.640
it has increased in 20 years.

01:03:34.600 --> 01:03:39.880
Let's say farm GDP, which is 17%-18%…
I think that's the number, 16% to 18%,

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:44.800
which comes around $550-$600
billion at this level.

01:03:44.880 --> 01:03:51.160
But that farm income
is only happening in tier 2 and beyond.

01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:54.560 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:00.720
80% of it.

01:04:01.720 --> 01:04:05.120
But those numbers, even because…
No tax and all.

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:08.892
On PPP, I think it's around,
if you'll see,

01:04:08.972 --> 01:04:12.160
it can create a $800-$900 billion
kind of impact.

01:04:12.240 --> 01:04:13.600
That's a huge number.

01:04:13.680 --> 01:04:15.280 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:04:15.360 --> 01:04:16.400
Value addition…

01:04:16.480 --> 01:04:20.600 line:1%
[both speaking in Hindi]

01:04:27.760 --> 01:04:29.120
Ultimately, you need X amount…

01:04:29.200 --> 01:04:31.120
The best consumption happens
when the economy is

01:04:31.200 --> 01:04:36.080
around $7,000 to $11,000 per person.

01:04:36.160 --> 01:04:39.600
Earlier, it was $4,000,
now people say it is $5,000 or $6,000.

01:04:39.680 --> 01:04:42.160 line:1%
-I would say… per capita.
-[Sujeet] Per capita.

01:04:42.240 --> 01:04:44.160 line:1%
[Nikhil] But do you think
that's the main metric that matters,

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:45.240 line:1%
per capita GDP?

01:04:45.320 --> 01:04:47.440 line:1%
Per capita matters a lot.

01:04:47.520 --> 01:04:51.160
Even when you are calculating
per capita GDP,

01:04:51.240 --> 01:04:53.920
you're taking total GDP
and dividing by population?

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.160
No, you remove some bit of it.

01:04:56.240 --> 01:04:59.560
So, it is around 2,700, currently.

01:04:59.640 --> 01:05:00.920
How do you arrive at that number, though?

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:03.960
Do you think the total,
divide by population?

01:05:04.040 --> 01:05:06.760
The average people use,
which is 2,000, is with that.

01:05:06.840 --> 01:05:08.400
That would skew everything, right?

01:05:08.480 --> 01:05:10.200
But yeah, the distribution,
which is what you come to.

01:05:10.280 --> 01:05:12.280
There are so many economies
within that economy.

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:15.240
Yeah, the government said that
it was 2,500 recently, but….

01:05:15.320 --> 01:05:17.280 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:05:20.800 --> 01:05:22.280 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:05:22.360 --> 01:05:25.005
If you take out your Ambani and Adani
from the top,

01:05:25.085 --> 01:05:26.520
it's a completely different…

01:05:26.600 --> 01:05:29.800
-It's a massive Pareto.
-It's a 10/80.

01:05:29.880 --> 01:05:34.600
India is a very, very interesting…
Another statistic which I want to…

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:37.200
India has two crore weddings a year.

01:05:37.280 --> 01:05:39.600
As in, one crore weddings,
two crore families.

01:05:39.680 --> 01:05:43.320
We produce 2.5 crore children every year.

01:05:43.400 --> 01:05:46.000
And our wedding economy is 15 lakh crores.

01:05:46.080 --> 01:05:47.760
Average spend of 7 lakh rupees
in a family,

01:05:47.840 --> 01:05:49.840
multiplied by two crore families
is 14 lakh crores.

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:52.120 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:05:52.200 --> 01:05:57.000 line:1%
[both speaking in Hindi]

01:05:57.080 --> 01:05:59.480
There is not one dominant player
or three-four dominant players.

01:05:59.560 --> 01:06:02.440
[in Hindi] India is so heterogenous,
so it's going on the way it does.

01:06:02.520 --> 01:06:04.080
[in Hindi] You cannot customize weddings.

01:06:04.160 --> 01:06:07.080 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:06:07.160 --> 01:06:10.040
But do you think it's an
opportunity, weddings?

01:06:10.120 --> 01:06:12.840
People have created,
made that into a business.

01:06:12.920 --> 01:06:16.120
Look at Manyavar as a brand now.
It is built on weddings.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:17.360
Manyavar is wedding aggregation.

01:06:17.440 --> 01:06:19.880
And there might be many, many brands.
Every city has brands.

01:06:19.960 --> 01:06:22.123
But still, if you look at
15 lakh crores scale,

01:06:22.203 --> 01:06:23.600
and then you look at Manyavar,

01:06:23.680 --> 01:06:25.880 line:1%
it doesn't feel proportionate, right?

01:06:25.960 --> 01:06:28.320 line:1%
[Sujeet and Kishore speaking in Hindi]

01:06:34.920 --> 01:06:39.480
In India, consumption is driven by
a lot of societal events.

01:06:39.560 --> 01:06:41.080
Look at the harvesting festival,

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:43.800
There, consumption used to happen
during harvesting,

01:06:43.880 --> 01:06:45.760
which talks about your
agricultural economy.

01:06:45.840 --> 01:06:47.720 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:06:49.360 --> 01:06:51.960 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:06:52.040 --> 01:06:57.640
I think the IT/technology business
created around how many people?

01:06:57.720 --> 01:07:02.200
Nearly crore-plus families
would have gotten into that business.

01:07:02.280 --> 01:07:04.120
And that created a lot of consumption.

01:07:04.200 --> 01:07:06.520
We need next round of economy…

01:07:06.600 --> 01:07:08.200
What do you think the next round will be?

01:07:08.280 --> 01:07:10.880
I think we will have to participate
in something…

01:07:10.960 --> 01:07:13.006
I think the creative economy
is a big economy

01:07:13.086 --> 01:07:15.040
which is creator economy,
creative economy.

01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:16.680
India can excel there also.

01:07:16.760 --> 01:07:19.600
We are fascinated by the generative AI.
Very, very fascinated.

01:07:19.680 --> 01:07:22.640
Imagine in retail business,
in a grocery business,

01:07:22.720 --> 01:07:27.000
somebody will tell that that they want
to make this item for the next five days…

01:07:27.080 --> 01:07:31.560
the retailer will give exact quantity
of what you want.

01:07:31.640 --> 01:07:34.360
So, the packaging will change,
everything will change.

01:07:36.520 --> 01:07:40.320
Any new technology
will bring in so many changes.

01:07:40.400 --> 01:07:42.640
The whole ecosystem around it changes.

01:07:42.720 --> 01:07:44.280
Also, another question.

01:07:44.360 --> 01:07:46.760
I'm gonna come to both of you and ask…

01:07:46.840 --> 01:07:50.160
What are the trends for the future,
and what do you see changing?

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:54.280
But since you three have worked
so much in this space…

01:07:55.160 --> 01:07:56.760
At the core of it…

01:07:57.600 --> 01:07:59.320 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:07:59.400 --> 01:08:03.160
Why does something sell?
And why does something not sell?

01:08:03.240 --> 01:08:07.600
If you had to provide insights from that,
what would you say?

01:08:07.680 --> 01:08:09.360
Maybe you can start first.

01:08:10.040 --> 01:08:12.720
I think a product sells

01:08:12.800 --> 01:08:16.480
because it fulfills the needs
of the customer.

01:08:16.560 --> 01:08:18.040
So what we used to say is

01:08:18.120 --> 01:08:20.800
there is a daily want,
and there is a daily need of a customer.

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:23.000
And there is occasional want,
and occasional needs.

01:08:23.080 --> 01:08:25.280
So your product has to fit in somewhere.

01:08:25.360 --> 01:08:28.440
And there are occasional consumptions,
and there are daily consumptions.

01:08:28.520 --> 01:08:32.113
Your product has to solve
the needs of that customer,

01:08:32.193 --> 01:08:34.040
the wants of that customer.

01:08:34.120 --> 01:08:37.080
Secondly, a product sells because

01:08:37.160 --> 01:08:39.960
you are fulfilling some vanity
or some ego of that person,

01:08:40.040 --> 01:08:42.720
if you are selling a high-value product.

01:08:42.800 --> 01:08:46.240
So how do you recognize these needs?

01:08:46.320 --> 01:08:49.240
If I am somebody who wants
to sell a product today,

01:08:49.320 --> 01:08:54.838
how will I get data
on what cures somebody's ego or vanity,

01:08:54.918 --> 01:08:56.480
what is his need?

01:08:56.560 --> 01:09:00.120
How do I go about figuring out
what product to design?

01:09:00.200 --> 01:09:03.280
I think the society is changing,
the world is changing.

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:07.520
You can look at what is getting popular.

01:09:07.600 --> 01:09:11.800
So… Like, we always thought
when OTT came in,

01:09:11.880 --> 01:09:16.040
and COVID made it happen that people
watched the longer form of storytelling,

01:09:16.120 --> 01:09:20.280
nobody believed that storytelling
can be told in 10 hours or 20 hours.

01:09:20.360 --> 01:09:24.240
Storytelling was supposed to be
within less than three hours.

01:09:24.320 --> 01:09:25.640
It changed the whole market.

01:09:25.720 --> 01:09:28.520
I think the whole content market,
the cinema, the multiplexes,

01:09:28.600 --> 01:09:31.720
it will undergo a significant change.

01:09:31.800 --> 01:09:35.920
So… now what to produce
which the customer or the audience likes?

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:38.600
Today, the entire Hindi
Bollywood film industry is struggling.

01:09:39.360 --> 01:09:42.200
There was a movie, I am told,
it didn't run for even a day.

01:09:43.120 --> 01:09:44.120
They had to take it out.

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:46.840
And these kind of mishaps
are happening like crazy.

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:47.920
[Sujeet] Yeah.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:50.480
So what do you create
for multiplexes as content?

01:09:51.400 --> 01:09:54.520
I think everybody
is getting to the drawing board, uh…

01:09:54.600 --> 01:09:57.040
By the way, this is true for retail
very, very strongly.

01:09:57.120 --> 01:10:00.320
I've seen… when the channel changes,
what sells also changes.

01:10:00.400 --> 01:10:01.560
[Kishore] Yeah, absolutely.

01:10:01.640 --> 01:10:02.920
-Always. Right?
-Absolutely.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:06.920
Because as soon as the channel changes,
like, what you discover first…

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:10.080
For example, earlier,
when you used to go offline,

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:13.040
you would touch the product,
that was a big part of what you buy.

01:10:13.120 --> 01:10:14.640
Now you can't do it, right?

01:10:14.720 --> 01:10:16.720
So, suddenly, pricing takes a big…

01:10:16.800 --> 01:10:20.400
Like, I have seen, online,
pricing suddenly is a lot more important

01:10:20.480 --> 01:10:24.320
because touch and quality is somehow…
it's very hard to pick.

01:10:24.400 --> 01:10:26.114
Now merchandising, inspiration,

01:10:26.194 --> 01:10:29.720
photographs, social matters a lot,
which was not there earlier.

01:10:29.800 --> 01:10:31.920
So, as soon as channel changes,

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:36.440
like, your… what sells changes,
like, completely.

01:10:37.320 --> 01:10:39.963
Now Internet was a big thing,
mobile was a big thing.

01:10:40.043 --> 01:10:42.160
Now AI, I don't know what that is, right?

01:10:42.240 --> 01:10:45.480
AI will also kind of change
some of these channels.

01:10:45.560 --> 01:10:47.360
-[Kishore] Absolutely.
-Meta was supposed to be…

01:10:47.440 --> 01:10:49.440
Now it doesn't feel like
it is gonna happen any time soon.

01:10:49.520 --> 01:10:50.520
But if that happened…

01:10:50.600 --> 01:10:53.360
…has a good…
has big potential in shopping?

01:10:53.440 --> 01:10:54.960
It should be.

01:10:55.040 --> 01:10:57.640
If medium becomes large, by the way,
then the channel…

01:10:57.720 --> 01:10:59.080
especially for shopping will change.

01:10:59.160 --> 01:11:01.160
But then what you buy
will be very different.

01:11:01.240 --> 01:11:03.840
If these guys, like Meta,

01:11:03.920 --> 01:11:06.920
with all the access to so much information

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:10.760
is spending $15 billion
or $16 billion a year

01:11:10.840 --> 01:11:12.640
on creating that ecosystem…

01:11:14.280 --> 01:11:17.320
would you say it's likely that
that will be the future?

01:11:17.400 --> 01:11:19.560
It's… It's very hard.

01:11:19.640 --> 01:11:22.680
Because historically, if you see,
whenever big technology shifts come,

01:11:22.760 --> 01:11:24.338
they generally don't come
from large companies,

01:11:24.418 --> 01:11:25.480
they come from start-ups, right?

01:11:25.560 --> 01:11:30.200
It's very hard that they will know
what people need… Meta will know, right?

01:11:30.280 --> 01:11:33.920
Like, that's a… Like, every single time,
all of these technologies that come,

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:36.520
they have never come
from existing large incumbents, right?

01:11:36.600 --> 01:11:39.880
So I find it unlikely that it'll happen.
It may happen. Like, who knows?

01:11:40.760 --> 01:11:44.160
-But historically, it's never been.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:11:44.960 --> 01:11:48.600
And what do you think…
Like I was asking him,

01:11:48.680 --> 01:11:51.360
what do you think is working today,

01:11:51.440 --> 01:11:54.640
and what do you think will work tomorrow
when it comes to selling a product?

01:11:55.360 --> 01:11:59.320
So I think I… Again, my assessment is…

01:11:59.400 --> 01:12:01.446
this whole thing of serving need

01:12:01.526 --> 01:12:04.680
has become a lot more of
serving aspirations now.

01:12:04.760 --> 01:12:05.883
As I was saying, most people come…

01:12:05.963 --> 01:12:07.360
[Nikhil] Is that because
society is changing?

01:12:07.440 --> 01:12:11.960
So, both. People now have a lot more
discretionary income, as people say.

01:12:12.040 --> 01:12:14.320
So it's not that when they want
to buy, they buy.

01:12:15.040 --> 01:12:16.640
Now people open the app,

01:12:16.720 --> 01:12:19.640
and they want to look like this celebrity
or look like this influencer

01:12:19.720 --> 01:12:21.360
because they feel it's much better.

01:12:21.440 --> 01:12:24.160
And they fulfill their aspiration,
they feel much more happier.

01:12:24.240 --> 01:12:27.240
Right? So now, I think some bit of that
consumption has started to happen.

01:12:27.320 --> 01:12:30.800
And we're still talking about
that 15-20 crore population of India?

01:12:30.880 --> 01:12:32.907
Like, for example,
just in the last 12 months,

01:12:32.987 --> 01:12:34.520
14 crore people have gotten Meesho.

01:12:34.600 --> 01:12:37.160
-So I'm saying it's a large…
-They go to a much larger audience.

01:12:37.240 --> 01:12:39.640
So now… It's a lot of people who are…

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:42.440
Like the India 2 is there.

01:12:42.520 --> 01:12:44.560
We have a lot of India 2 users
on our platform.

01:12:44.640 --> 01:12:48.960
So you're saying, is Meesho predominantly
India 1 with some India 2

01:12:49.040 --> 01:12:50.760
or is it like India 1 plus India 2?

01:12:50.840 --> 01:12:52.880
I would say both. Both, balanced.

01:12:52.960 --> 01:12:55.520
We don't have… India 1 is
a very broad segment, right?

01:12:55.600 --> 01:12:58.640
So we don't have the top 10-15 million,
I would say. But everyone else after.

01:12:58.720 --> 01:13:01.760
Do you see India 2's
discretionary income rising?

01:13:01.840 --> 01:13:03.800
So… it's still small.

01:13:03.880 --> 01:13:06.800
And that's why our job is to, like,
within that small wallet,

01:13:06.880 --> 01:13:08.680
still help them fulfill those aspirations.

01:13:08.760 --> 01:13:11.080
They still go on Instagram,
they still follow someone.

01:13:11.160 --> 01:13:13.080
And they say, "Hey, no,
I don't have the same amount of money,

01:13:13.160 --> 01:13:16.160
"can you help me fulfill this aspiration
in a very small budget?"

01:13:16.240 --> 01:13:17.680
Which is what we solve.

01:13:17.760 --> 01:13:19.960
But they also have aspirations.
Very, very strong ones.

01:13:20.040 --> 01:13:22.440
No, we had a very interesting…
another theory.

01:13:22.520 --> 01:13:25.400
Like, India 1 consumes in their lifetime…

01:13:25.480 --> 01:13:29.160
I would have consumed
at least 10,000 SKUs.

01:13:29.240 --> 01:13:32.600
Uh, but India 2 or India 3…

01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:35.300
India 3 will be 200 SKUs.

01:13:35.380 --> 01:13:38.200
India 2 would be, I don't know how much,

01:13:38.280 --> 01:13:41.440
but not more than 400-500
in their lifetime.

01:13:42.160 --> 01:13:43.840
-That's rising.
-[Vidit] Correct.

01:13:43.920 --> 01:13:47.520
I would say India 2 would have consumed
only 100 SKUs at one point of time,

01:13:47.600 --> 01:13:49.480
-now it's rising.
-[Vidit] Going up.

01:13:49.560 --> 01:13:50.773
Now they want from that,

01:13:50.853 --> 01:13:53.320
to a toothpaste, to this,
to a cream, to everything.

01:13:53.400 --> 01:13:55.200
So that's… that's happening.

01:13:55.280 --> 01:13:58.687
So you're saying it makes sense
to build products

01:13:58.767 --> 01:14:01.400
which appear to be aspirational today.

01:14:01.480 --> 01:14:03.560
And what do you think will be tomorrow?

01:14:05.240 --> 01:14:10.720
It's very hard. I just feel like
a lot of this as per capita goes up,

01:14:10.800 --> 01:14:12.920
this 2,000 goes to 4,000,

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:15.800
most of the increase is happening
in discretionary, and not like…

01:14:15.880 --> 01:14:19.560
People fulfill their
non-discretionary needs anyway, right?

01:14:19.640 --> 01:14:20.960
So, it's gonna come here.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:23.920
So I feel this aspirational thing
is gonna compound

01:14:24.000 --> 01:14:26.440
and grow non-linearly going forward.

01:14:26.520 --> 01:14:29.160
Like, everyone is doing it,
and everyone is doing it individually now.

01:14:29.240 --> 01:14:30.613
So, earlier it used to be a family affair,

01:14:30.693 --> 01:14:32.720
now everyone is fulfilling
their own aspirations separately.

01:14:32.800 --> 01:14:34.800
Everyone follows someone else
on Instagram.

01:14:34.880 --> 01:14:37.640
Everyone else has different things
that they aspire for.

01:14:37.720 --> 01:14:39.640
And they are fulfilling it
again and again.

01:14:39.720 --> 01:14:42.640
And our job is
to basically make it affordable.

01:14:42.720 --> 01:14:47.520
Right? Like, how do we make them
achieve their aspirations affordably

01:14:47.600 --> 01:14:49.640
is what we focus on as a company.

01:14:49.720 --> 01:14:52.240
Right, right. Do you wanna go next?

01:14:52.320 --> 01:14:55.920
Yeah, like, it's a very complex thing.

01:14:56.000 --> 01:14:59.040
-If you'll see…
-What trend is working today…

01:14:59.120 --> 01:15:03.120
So if I am building a product for today,
what do you think I should keep in mind?

01:15:03.200 --> 01:15:06.520
And what trend do you think
will be there tomorrow?

01:15:06.600 --> 01:15:09.198
Today… [clears throat]

01:15:09.278 --> 01:15:13.920
If you'll see, it's a…
If you are talking about commerce,

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:17.880
it drives from your unit economics,
am I right?

01:15:17.960 --> 01:15:21.480
Currently, it's making
lots of sense to optimize,

01:15:21.560 --> 01:15:24.560
let's say on supply chain,
sourcing, inventory…

01:15:24.640 --> 01:15:27.000
And everywhere, the technology goes.

01:15:27.080 --> 01:15:30.320
There's a festival, these SKUs go.

01:15:30.400 --> 01:15:34.181
So, currently, we are picking off
which SKU, how, what,

01:15:34.261 --> 01:15:35.680
and all those things.

01:15:35.760 --> 01:15:39.640
We are building a technology,
infrastructure,

01:15:39.720 --> 01:15:43.440
consumption, predicting,
"Hey, next time, next year,

01:15:43.520 --> 01:15:45.880
"40% it will grow in this channel."

01:15:45.960 --> 01:15:49.680
But how channels are changing, it's…

01:15:49.760 --> 01:15:50.760
it's very different.

01:15:50.840 --> 01:15:53.040
Like, I was just describing,

01:15:53.120 --> 01:15:55.480
Gen Zs are thinking
in a very different way…

01:15:56.320 --> 01:15:58.280
about their consumption.

01:15:58.360 --> 01:16:03.000
Um, millennials are definitely
a bit thinking,

01:16:03.080 --> 01:16:06.120
and the other… like traditional consumers

01:16:06.200 --> 01:16:09.240
who are price-sensitive, quality,
touch and feel.

01:16:09.320 --> 01:16:12.600
I'll give one example,
a Gen Z was saying that,

01:16:12.680 --> 01:16:15.960
"Size matters too much to me.

01:16:16.040 --> 01:16:18.760
"I am not going to buy online."

01:16:18.840 --> 01:16:21.080
-[in Hindi] What were they talking about?
-Clothing size.

01:16:22.320 --> 01:16:25.520
Sorry. So, "I am not going to buy online,

01:16:25.600 --> 01:16:29.040
"because, for me,
I am buying and then returning again.

01:16:29.120 --> 01:16:33.280
"I wanted it to fit and look
exactly like the celebrity."

01:16:33.360 --> 01:16:38.120
"So, for me, the price-sensitivity
is not that much, for me these…

01:16:38.200 --> 01:16:40.840
"And offline gives me that flexibility.

01:16:41.760 --> 01:16:46.480
"So, I will see here,
but I want to buy what I like offline.

01:16:46.560 --> 01:16:50.200
"Because that is instant,
if I am able to buy offline."

01:16:50.920 --> 01:16:53.200
So, it's a different kind of…
I never imagined…

01:16:53.280 --> 01:16:54.600
Because there are so many policies,

01:16:54.680 --> 01:16:58.200
we are saying that, "Hey, I will return
within five days, ten days."

01:16:58.280 --> 01:17:02.240
Again, fulfill…
No, no, it will not matter.

01:17:02.320 --> 01:17:04.520
For me, it takes a lot of time.

01:17:04.600 --> 01:17:08.480
Either I should order five, six sizes…

01:17:08.560 --> 01:17:10.480
then my money gets stuck.

01:17:11.600 --> 01:17:15.440
The insight is that we have to watch out

01:17:15.520 --> 01:17:19.280
where the consumers are spending
most of their time.

01:17:20.040 --> 01:17:23.960
And we have to build some of the products
according to that channel.

01:17:24.040 --> 01:17:27.320
So, if you see, most of the evolution,
and sir will agree…

01:17:29.240 --> 01:17:31.520
has happened in technology on the backend,

01:17:32.600 --> 01:17:36.200
rationalizing the technology
for applications like

01:17:36.280 --> 01:17:38.520
what to give to consumers,

01:17:38.600 --> 01:17:43.480
like pricing search, SKU search,
cataloguing, things like that.

01:17:43.560 --> 01:17:46.080
All those investments have happened
in the last 15 years,

01:17:46.160 --> 01:17:47.840
I can at least say that.

01:17:48.680 --> 01:17:52.120
But nobody knows
which channel is picking up.

01:17:53.040 --> 01:17:57.680
So I think that's where I am saying,
now the time is to find a consumer,

01:17:57.760 --> 01:18:01.840
their money, where they are liking,
what's their liking, every…-

01:18:01.920 --> 01:18:03.360
Like, for fashion…

01:18:05.240 --> 01:18:09.880
Logically, let's say, social media
is one of the most leading channels.

01:18:09.960 --> 01:18:13.520
But for consumer goods, like white goods,

01:18:14.280 --> 01:18:19.720
is it the performance? Is it the support?
Is it the pricing? I don't know.

01:18:19.800 --> 01:18:24.120
Let's say, buying AC on social media
is very hard to imagine.

01:18:25.240 --> 01:18:29.160
Mobile phone, I am very clear
because it's feature-led. Camera-led.

01:18:29.240 --> 01:18:34.560
Camera is dominating mobile as a category,
because that's the consideration set

01:18:34.640 --> 01:18:37.480
for the new generation
as well as everyone else.

01:18:37.560 --> 01:18:40.520
Say your son grows up in five years,
and he's shopping…

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:42.880
I don't know. He will buy something
within the game.

01:18:42.960 --> 01:18:46.320
-He's playing…
-[Vidit and Kishore chuckle]

01:18:46.400 --> 01:18:49.560
He can click, "I wanted to order this,
I wanted to look like this."

01:18:50.640 --> 01:18:52.160
I don't know.

01:18:52.240 --> 01:18:54.920
-Might be that's not the mainstream.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:18:55.800 --> 01:18:58.760
Another question I wanted to ask is…

01:18:58.840 --> 01:19:02.560
When aggregation happens
even in between platforms,

01:19:02.640 --> 01:19:05.440
like, soon maybe we will get to a point

01:19:05.520 --> 01:19:07.960
where Meesho is selling
everything that is available,

01:19:08.040 --> 01:19:10.920
Amazon is selling everything
that is available,

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:13.840
Udaan, Flipkart, everybody…

01:19:14.862 --> 01:19:19.342
will it come down to curation
and legitimacy in a way

01:19:19.440 --> 01:19:22.320
as to how I pick
which platform to shop on?

01:19:22.400 --> 01:19:26.520
By the way, it ends up being
what your value prop is.

01:19:26.600 --> 01:19:30.520
So, for example,
Amazon is very, very focused on…

01:19:30.600 --> 01:19:32.640
So, tell me about everybody,
because you're in this.

01:19:32.720 --> 01:19:35.480
Finish with Meesho.
What is Amazon's value proposition?

01:19:35.560 --> 01:19:38.680
Amazon's is, like, convenience.
So, I wanna stand for convenience, right?

01:19:38.760 --> 01:19:40.880
So, they will make sure
that everything that you order,

01:19:40.960 --> 01:19:44.480
you always feel like it comes faster here,
as compared to anyone else.

01:19:44.560 --> 01:19:47.568
But the flip side is that
often the product is fake

01:19:47.648 --> 01:19:49.880
and the quality checks are not at par.

01:19:49.960 --> 01:19:51.379
It could be. Right?
And that, by the way,

01:19:51.459 --> 01:19:53.480
it's a thing that
they will continue to improve.

01:19:53.560 --> 01:19:56.800
But one thing they want to stand for,
which is this, convenience. Right?

01:19:56.880 --> 01:19:58.589
And everything else
if you ask me is secondary.

01:19:58.669 --> 01:20:00.080
They'll continue
to make some improvements.

01:20:00.160 --> 01:20:02.680
It's not like you have to
achieve excellence here.

01:20:02.760 --> 01:20:04.518
But they're gonna do this,
they're gonna stand for it.

01:20:04.598 --> 01:20:06.806
They will not sell anything
where this somehow gets diluted.

01:20:06.886 --> 01:20:07.880
Because of the brand, right?

01:20:07.960 --> 01:20:10.440
The value add
that people remember you for is that.

01:20:10.520 --> 01:20:12.480
When they come to Meesho, people believe,

01:20:12.560 --> 01:20:17.080
"This selection, I will not get for, uh,
a more affordable price anywhere else."

01:20:17.160 --> 01:20:18.840
They have to believe this.

01:20:18.920 --> 01:20:20.962
And I will get
the largest possible selection

01:20:21.042 --> 01:20:22.760
in the price points that I can afford.

01:20:22.840 --> 01:20:24.440
That also I have to believe.

01:20:24.520 --> 01:20:26.920
Now, everything we do in our business,
basically…

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:30.880
I don't know, I think it is
a category-wise difference, and maybe…

01:20:30.960 --> 01:20:33.280
[Nikhil] What is Flipkart
and Amazon's distinction?

01:20:34.360 --> 01:20:35.944
[Sujeet] I think…
-For a long time,

01:20:36.024 --> 01:20:37.920
if I have to tell you the truth,

01:20:38.001 --> 01:20:41.970
I bought stuff on Flipkart
out of some stupid notion

01:20:42.050 --> 01:20:44.360
that they're an Indian company
and nationalism.

01:20:44.440 --> 01:20:46.040
But now, after Walmart deal,

01:20:46.120 --> 01:20:49.040
I don't see any distinction
between Flipkart and Walmart.

01:20:49.120 --> 01:20:53.400
I would just as well buy on Amazon
as I might on Flipkart.

01:20:53.480 --> 01:20:55.440
How does Flipkart distinguish itself?

01:20:55.520 --> 01:20:58.320
I think the DNA of the company,
I can definitely talk about.

01:20:58.400 --> 01:21:00.080
I think we were building the…

01:21:02.523 --> 01:21:06.240
company, it was like "How to give
the best value proposition?"

01:21:06.320 --> 01:21:10.080
Let's say prices, service, let's say COD,

01:21:10.160 --> 01:21:13.120
building logistics around that,
something like that. Am I right?

01:21:13.200 --> 01:21:16.200
Would you put that
in the category of convenience

01:21:16.280 --> 01:21:18.480
and say Flipkart thought that
there is room for two players?

01:21:18.560 --> 01:21:20.120
Value proposition could be pricing.

01:21:20.200 --> 01:21:22.720
-Like, it's good price, like that.
-[Nikhil] Hmm.

01:21:24.157 --> 01:21:28.640
Definitely, price has lots of aspects,
I am not going into that,

01:21:28.720 --> 01:21:32.560
but offering what Indian consumer wants…

01:21:32.640 --> 01:21:36.640
I think Amazon has, like he was saying,
that convenience.

01:21:36.720 --> 01:21:41.840
But that audience, even in bucket A,
is very narrow.

01:21:41.937 --> 01:21:43.120
What do you think about multiplexes?

01:21:43.200 --> 01:21:44.840
This is a good segue
into a very interesting question.

01:21:44.920 --> 01:21:47.720
I remember you owned a bit of multiplexes.

01:21:47.800 --> 01:21:51.880
I still have. I have reduced
my shareholding, I have about 2%.

01:21:51.960 --> 01:21:54.480
-And I keep asking a lot of…
-[Vidit] Of PVR?

01:21:54.560 --> 01:21:56.440
I was on the board of INOX
for a long time.

01:21:56.520 --> 01:21:58.600
[Nikhil] Now they have merged,
PVR and INOX have merged.

01:21:58.680 --> 01:22:01.080
So, you'd know. You should tell us this.
Like, you are interrogating us.

01:22:01.160 --> 01:22:02.720
I think you should also answer
some of these.

01:22:02.800 --> 01:22:04.720
You tell us what's gonna happen
in multiplexes.

01:22:04.800 --> 01:22:05.800
I'll tell you, truly.

01:22:05.880 --> 01:22:08.840
What were your beliefs,
and why did you choose it?

01:22:09.440 --> 01:22:13.640
My tryst with multiplex companies
started many years ago. Okay?

01:22:13.720 --> 01:22:20.160
Like, maybe six or seven years ago,
I had a very bearish outlook of them.

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:22.160
Six-seven years ago, pre-pandemic.

01:22:22.240 --> 01:22:24.440
Much, much before pandemic.

01:22:24.520 --> 01:22:29.960
I shorted them to begin with
when PVR was at 1,300 bucks, 1,400 bucks.

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:34.080
There were a couple of policy changes
which were happening,

01:22:34.160 --> 01:22:37.680
the foremost of them being, uh…

01:22:37.760 --> 01:22:39.880
it was in court
that people will be allowed

01:22:39.960 --> 01:22:42.400
to bring outside food and water,

01:22:42.480 --> 01:22:45.240
and drink it inside the multiplex
and eat it.

01:22:45.320 --> 01:22:49.400
And food as an income source
for multiplexes is really high.

01:22:49.480 --> 01:22:51.280
As high as 40-45%.

01:22:52.200 --> 01:22:57.600
Then it changed pre-pandemic
when I went long on these companies,

01:22:58.880 --> 01:23:05.240
because my reasoning changed to India 2,
like sir mentioned, is growing.

01:23:05.320 --> 01:23:10.720
In terms of entertainment
for a family of four for three hours

01:23:10.800 --> 01:23:13.360
at sub-Rs 1,000

01:23:13.440 --> 01:23:16.600
in a safe air-conditioned environment,

01:23:16.680 --> 01:23:18.320
the alternatives were not many.

01:23:18.400 --> 01:23:20.960
One could argue that cricket
is an alternative,

01:23:21.960 --> 01:23:24.400
but I thought as India 2 grows,

01:23:24.480 --> 01:23:28.640
the relevance of multiplex will go up,

01:23:28.720 --> 01:23:30.604
and they also become
these distribution hubs,

01:23:30.684 --> 01:23:32.480
which I don't think they have
up until now,

01:23:32.560 --> 01:23:34.440
but if people are going there so often,

01:23:34.520 --> 01:23:37.800
it gives them the opportunity
to do other kind of marketing.

01:23:37.880 --> 01:23:40.160
branding, advertising, all kinds of stuff.

01:23:41.120 --> 01:23:45.520
Where I sit today, I am confused.
Like everything else in my life,

01:23:45.600 --> 01:23:48.600
I'm shrouded in ambiguity on both sides,

01:23:48.680 --> 01:23:52.400
because when I talk to people who…

01:23:52.480 --> 01:23:58.280
Say, when I talk to somebody
who is the CEO of Hotstar.

01:23:58.360 --> 01:24:00.144
He's… Now the Bangalore guy, right?

01:24:00.224 --> 01:24:01.800 line:1%
Like Sajith has become the CEO.

01:24:01.880 --> 01:24:04.320 line:1%
The ex-Google Pay guy.

01:24:04.400 --> 01:24:06.920
[Sujeet] Sajith is also our neighbor.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:13.880
Yeah, so he would give me an outlook
of why OTT will kill traditional cinema.

01:24:14.680 --> 01:24:18.600
But then, I talked to somebody
like a UFO Movies,

01:24:18.680 --> 01:24:20.600
which is also another company
I have invested in.

01:24:20.680 --> 01:24:25.760
They manage the technology around
projecting the movie on the screen.

01:24:25.840 --> 01:24:28.280
There I start to think,

01:24:29.120 --> 01:24:31.640
the number of screens available,

01:24:31.720 --> 01:24:35.840
the density of screens in India
is still, like, much, much lower.

01:24:35.920 --> 01:24:37.720
Like, I would say in the US,

01:24:37.800 --> 01:24:41.440
there is one multiplex screen
for 30,000-40,000 people.

01:24:41.520 --> 01:24:46.120
In China, maybe for a few
hundred thousand people.

01:24:46.200 --> 01:24:51.240
In India, there is one screen for many,
many hundreds of thousands of people.

01:24:51.320 --> 01:24:55.680
And to a large part of India,
watching a movie is still going…

01:24:55.760 --> 01:24:58.480
[in Hindi] You know, that truck
comes with a screen in the villages,

01:24:58.560 --> 01:25:00.520
and then everybody gets together?

01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:05.200
With no kind of choice
as to what content they get to watch.

01:25:05.280 --> 01:25:09.040
-So, for me…
-[Vidit] But on this last point,

01:25:09.120 --> 01:25:11.240
as Kishore ji was saying,

01:25:11.320 --> 01:25:14.480
anywhere where you use
the population number is somewhat…

01:25:14.560 --> 01:25:19.200
the "per X number of people" has a lot
of India 3 which skews this metric.

01:25:19.280 --> 01:25:21.520
How do you get to the right number?

01:25:21.600 --> 01:25:24.920
Secondly, people believe that India 2
wants to come into India 1.

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:26.000
I don't think so.

01:25:26.800 --> 01:25:31.400
Societally, they look down upon us.

01:25:31.480 --> 01:25:33.840
I also think that's the right way.

01:25:33.920 --> 01:25:39.680
I feel like we follow or we try to follow
on the path of the West and China so much,

01:25:39.760 --> 01:25:44.680
by thinking that everybody
moving into cities,

01:25:44.760 --> 01:25:47.760
all of this is good for the economy
and growth and all of that.

01:25:47.840 --> 01:25:50.360
I personally believe, for many reasons,

01:25:50.440 --> 01:25:55.160
fragmentation is actually a model
that could work better for today

01:25:55.240 --> 01:25:57.520
than it did for China 20-30 years ago.

01:25:57.600 --> 01:26:00.380
So, Nikhil, I want to say something
for this multiplex thing.

01:26:00.460 --> 01:26:03.880
You know, when mobile phone
came into the picture,

01:26:03.960 --> 01:26:06.360
and everybody wanted to buy
a mobile phone,

01:26:06.440 --> 01:26:07.760
where did the budget come from?

01:26:07.840 --> 01:26:09.960
-They had to reduce some spend somewhere.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:26:10.040 --> 01:26:11.811
And the biggest impact came on fashion.

01:26:11.891 --> 01:26:14.080
And we were a part
of the fashion business then.

01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:16.240
And people were changing phones
in the first six months.

01:26:16.320 --> 01:26:20.160
Everybody was changing phones
much, much faster. Now, it's slowed down.

01:26:20.240 --> 01:26:23.440
So, what has happened,
if you look at the multiplex industry,

01:26:23.520 --> 01:26:26.452
that money you have spent,
which was supposed to go to multiplexes,

01:26:26.532 --> 01:26:28.000
they are going to restaurants now.

01:26:28.840 --> 01:26:31.600
People are spending two and a half hours,
families sitting together,

01:26:31.680 --> 01:26:35.920
friends sitting together
and spending that Rs 1,500-2,000 per head.

01:26:36.000 --> 01:26:39.160
And that money is clearly seen.
People don't want to watch content.

01:26:39.240 --> 01:26:41.840
-Can I ask you another question here?
-[Kishore] Mm.

01:26:41.920 --> 01:26:44.680
Like, the listed restaurant chains,

01:26:44.760 --> 01:26:47.600
you take Jubilant, you take Westlife,

01:26:47.680 --> 01:26:50.400
take the franchises
of big Western counterparts,

01:26:50.480 --> 01:26:54.160
McDonald's, Burger King, KFC, all of that,

01:26:54.240 --> 01:26:58.440
they all command a significant premium
to the market, right?

01:26:58.520 --> 01:27:01.520
They trade at, let's say,

01:27:01.600 --> 01:27:05.880
they are earning Rs 100,
their valuation is 7,000, 8,000,

01:27:05.960 --> 01:27:08.520
in some cases 20,000, all of that…

01:27:09.800 --> 01:27:12.760
But the unlisted space in restaurants…

01:27:14.280 --> 01:27:17.440
what happens if somebody
comes in and aggregates?

01:27:17.520 --> 01:27:19.365
Like, we spoke about Saravana Bhavan,

01:27:19.445 --> 01:27:21.720
there are so many of these in India,
right?

01:27:21.800 --> 01:27:25.840
If somebody comes and aggregates
a bunch of these chains

01:27:25.920 --> 01:27:28.419
where the total sales comes up on par

01:27:28.499 --> 01:27:31.960
with, say, the Western counterparts
which have franchises,

01:27:32.040 --> 01:27:35.960
do you think there is an arbitrage
between the valuation of this to that?

01:27:36.040 --> 01:27:37.520
[Kishore] But they don't need money.

01:27:38.800 --> 01:27:40.880
Rameshwaram, why will he need money?

01:27:40.960 --> 01:27:43.320
They refuse to talk.

01:27:43.400 --> 01:27:46.440
It is impossible.
Because if you are a good business,

01:27:46.520 --> 01:27:48.480
you don't need money at all.

01:27:48.560 --> 01:27:49.960
But the question is,

01:27:50.040 --> 01:27:54.520
does a business often need money
in order to scale?

01:27:54.600 --> 01:27:57.840
-If that is the case, with more money…
-They don't want scale.

01:27:57.920 --> 01:28:01.680
We all assume that everybody wants scale.
I also thought similarly.

01:28:01.760 --> 01:28:04.320
If we want scale, we expect everybody…

01:28:04.400 --> 01:28:09.120
For the last one and a half years,
I have spent lots of time on this.

01:28:09.880 --> 01:28:12.900
Money-making businesses,
especially in this, restaurants,

01:28:12.980 --> 01:28:16.000
most of them make money,
especially the good ones whom we know.

01:28:17.560 --> 01:28:20.240
-80%, they don't want money.
-[Kishore] Yeah, yeah.

01:28:20.960 --> 01:28:22.720
They don't want to expand.

01:28:22.800 --> 01:28:24.800
And why don't they want to expand?

01:28:24.880 --> 01:28:27.951
They simply say,
"Our quality will deteriorate."

01:28:28.031 --> 01:28:30.000
"I don't want these headaches."

01:28:30.080 --> 01:28:33.160
"I don't want to dilute." They don't want.

01:28:33.240 --> 01:28:34.560
I think there are two categories,
there are…

01:28:34.640 --> 01:28:36.360
A few people who are defensive.

01:28:36.440 --> 01:28:38.440
But I'm sure there are people
who are aggressive also.

01:28:38.520 --> 01:28:40.480
By the way, people who you…
Let's say Vidyarthi Bhavan,

01:28:40.560 --> 01:28:41.640
go and talk to the owner.

01:28:41.720 --> 01:28:44.120
Yeah, but you see the experience.

01:28:44.200 --> 01:28:45.560
Such a big brand, then you go there

01:28:45.640 --> 01:28:48.120
and you have 100 people
who are standing outside.

01:28:48.200 --> 01:28:50.480
That guy does not know
how to monetize the asset.

01:28:50.560 --> 01:28:52.640
That is where the people are going.

01:28:52.720 --> 01:28:56.451
But I'll tell you, why are temples created
where there is no pain?

01:28:56.531 --> 01:28:58.720
Because without pain, there is no gain.

01:28:58.800 --> 01:29:00.240
[Vidit laughing]

01:29:00.320 --> 01:29:03.080
There are queues when you go the temple…

01:29:03.160 --> 01:29:06.080
-Have you gone to Rameshwaram Cafe?
-[Vidit] I have, I have.

01:29:06.160 --> 01:29:09.120
I go to Rameshwaram weekly,
and every time, I get amazed.

01:29:09.200 --> 01:29:12.080
Sometimes, there is
a 200 metre line at the billing.

01:29:12.160 --> 01:29:13.640
-[Vidit] You go to Indiranagar?
-Yes.

01:29:13.720 --> 01:29:16.200
I go to the one in Whitefield
which is a much larger place,

01:29:16.280 --> 01:29:17.520
you'll get to eat.

01:29:17.600 --> 01:29:20.320
No, I understand,
but Indiranagar is iconic.

01:29:21.560 --> 01:29:24.120
No, but at the core of it, right…

01:29:24.200 --> 01:29:26.640
I get the point you guys are making,

01:29:26.720 --> 01:29:33.240
but I like to believe that we live
in an aspirational capitalistic ecosystem.

01:29:33.320 --> 01:29:35.240
-[Vidit] Correct.
-Not as much as what we think.

01:29:35.320 --> 01:29:37.680
Yes. But to a certain extent,
we are capitalistic.

01:29:37.760 --> 01:29:40.520
There is no debate on that,
but it is not as much as we think.

01:29:40.600 --> 01:29:44.240
If somebody has the opportunity to expand

01:29:44.320 --> 01:29:48.780
and be a bigger winner
in the cycle of capitalism,

01:29:48.880 --> 01:29:53.280
I think human tendency will persuade him
in that direction, eventually.

01:29:53.360 --> 01:29:56.480
At whatever pace.
To whatever level of magnitude.

01:29:56.560 --> 01:30:01.200
New food and new things are showing,
but I don't know the reason.

01:30:01.280 --> 01:30:03.880
Like, I have my own experience
in restaurant business.

01:30:03.960 --> 01:30:05.671 line:1%
We came in too early like Silsila movie.

01:30:05.751 --> 01:30:07.200 line:1%
It was a little ahead of its time.

01:30:07.280 --> 01:30:08.840
[Vidit laughs]

01:30:08.920 --> 01:30:11.120
-I like your movie analogy.
-[Vidit] Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:30:11.200 --> 01:30:14.000
So, we used to run
most of the chains in Bombay.

01:30:14.080 --> 01:30:15.080
[Vidit] Ah!

01:30:15.160 --> 01:30:18.640
-Bombay Blues, Noodle Bar, Copper Chimney.
-[Sujeet] I got it. I know them.

01:30:18.720 --> 01:30:21.880
-Sports bars.
-[Sujeet] Ahead of time, ahead of time.

01:30:21.960 --> 01:30:24.640
Very ahead of its time.
And how much money we lost, we only know.

01:30:25.461 --> 01:30:27.680
But now I think it's the right time.

01:30:27.760 --> 01:30:29.616
The problem with restaurants is
that the per capita expenditure

01:30:29.696 --> 01:30:30.800
of building a restaurant is very high,

01:30:30.880 --> 01:30:33.920
and the life of a restaurant is very low.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:37.040
-I'm talking about QSR now.
-QSR, then you will be very successful.

01:30:37.120 --> 01:30:38.200
[Sujeet] Yeah.

01:30:38.841 --> 01:30:42.840
Is that why the franchise model
with so much standardization do better?

01:30:42.920 --> 01:30:46.520
It is the industrialization
of restaurants.

01:30:46.600 --> 01:30:47.880
-That's a QSR.
-[Kishore] Yeah.

01:30:47.961 --> 01:30:50.120
Not all QSRs, in a way.

01:30:50.182 --> 01:30:52.640
-Most of it.
-Yeah, most of it.

01:30:52.720 --> 01:30:55.200
Let say if I add Rameshwaram,
for me, it will be a QSR

01:30:55.280 --> 01:30:57.560
if I am going to scale it.

01:30:57.640 --> 01:31:00.160
But, that… [chuckles]

01:31:00.240 --> 01:31:01.960
-That's how I see it.
-[Kishore] Yeah.

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:05.960
But, you see, Rameshwaram
also gets an extra space outside

01:31:06.040 --> 01:31:08.280
for which he is not paying,
where people are standing and eating.

01:31:09.840 --> 01:31:10.840
So…

01:31:10.920 --> 01:31:12.640
I think there is a novelty
attached to that.

01:31:12.720 --> 01:31:14.680 line:1%
-Whenever you see…
-You won't find another place like that.

01:31:14.760 --> 01:31:18.520 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:31:18.600 --> 01:31:19.760
That is so true.

01:31:19.840 --> 01:31:21.120
[in Hindi] Like, if I had
to open a restaurant,

01:31:21.200 --> 01:31:24.520
I would only put five chairs inside
and request people to wait outside.

01:31:24.600 --> 01:31:27.920
That would probably give me more business
than having 40 chairs in there.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:29.560
-Correct.
-[Nikhil] In a weird way, that works.

01:31:31.102 --> 01:31:32.280
You never know.

01:31:33.040 --> 01:31:36.400
But food is a very interesting…
Indians love discovering new food.

01:31:36.480 --> 01:31:39.400
I'm telling you about this coffee chain.

01:31:39.480 --> 01:31:42.120
Two-three years back,

01:31:42.200 --> 01:31:45.160
no investor was willing to invest

01:31:45.240 --> 01:31:47.520
because they believe that…
[in Hindi] "It won't work in India."

01:31:48.643 --> 01:31:52.803
[in English] Now if you see what happened,
even I don't know why it is the way it is.

01:31:52.880 --> 01:31:54.901
But wherever these stores are opening,

01:31:54.981 --> 01:31:57.360
it doesn't matter if it is Bangalore
or Delhi or Mumbai…

01:31:57.440 --> 01:32:00.360
It is only in four-five cities,
they are going crazy.

01:32:02.403 --> 01:32:05.120
-I'm still finding that part…
-It's not about that.

01:32:05.200 --> 01:32:08.120
It's about people spending time,
it's a social interaction.

01:32:08.200 --> 01:32:11.360
Earlier also, it was that,
but nobody was believing it.

01:32:11.440 --> 01:32:13.400
It was on the verge of closing down.

01:32:13.480 --> 01:32:15.065
Coffee is one of the by-product

01:32:15.145 --> 01:32:17.360
of whatever other activities
you are doing.

01:32:17.440 --> 01:32:18.982
Maybe, sometimes, it is the main activity,

01:32:19.062 --> 01:32:20.680
but you tend to get to
the other activities.

01:32:20.760 --> 01:32:24.600
I agree with you 100%.
I'm also a small investor with him

01:32:24.680 --> 01:32:28.208
in Third Wave, Hatti Kaapi,
and a couple of coffee places.

01:32:28.288 --> 01:32:31.040
When I was reviewing coffee chains,

01:32:31.120 --> 01:32:33.680
and I was trying to do it
as objectively as I could,

01:32:33.760 --> 01:32:37.600
the difference between
the West and India is,

01:32:37.680 --> 01:32:40.160
in the West,
people are going into a coffee shop

01:32:40.240 --> 01:32:41.680
to actually drink coffee.

01:32:41.761 --> 01:32:45.680
The culture of buying a coffee
and walking, especially in New York,

01:32:45.760 --> 01:32:49.578
is such a big thing
that the financials work out for them.

01:32:49.658 --> 01:32:52.280
Here if you sell a coffee at Rs 200-300

01:32:52.360 --> 01:32:55.520
and people have to sit there
two hours to consume it,

01:32:55.600 --> 01:32:57.819
and you have to pay for the real estate,

01:32:57.899 --> 01:33:00.920
the numbers, you look at it
from a different light, altogether.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:04.151
So, I don't think
in that particular instance,

01:33:04.231 --> 01:33:05.680
especially in coffee,

01:33:05.760 --> 01:33:08.840
we can equate what happens here
to what happens in the West,

01:33:08.920 --> 01:33:10.440
to your earlier example,

01:33:10.520 --> 01:33:12.800
because I don't think
we will copy what they are doing.

01:33:14.062 --> 01:33:17.360
So you're saying it is harder
to make money here in coffee in India?

01:33:17.440 --> 01:33:19.840
Restaurants have just started
making money in India.

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:22.080
Yeah, but they have started making money.

01:33:22.160 --> 01:33:24.160
-Hmm?
-But they have started making money.

01:33:24.240 --> 01:33:25.920
QSR are making good money.

01:33:26.960 --> 01:33:29.720
-Good money…
-Early to say that, but let's see.

01:33:29.800 --> 01:33:32.360 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:33:32.440 --> 01:33:34.439
How much money
did you spend on your wedding?

01:33:34.519 --> 01:33:38.520
On my wedding? I spent very less, yeah.
This was like long ago, before…

01:33:38.600 --> 01:33:41.320
-[Sujeet] When did you get married?
-…I had raised any money, so…

01:33:44.560 --> 01:33:47.520
-When did you get married?
-I got married in 2018, beginning.

01:33:47.600 --> 01:33:50.680
-2018.
-[In Hindi] That's very recent. Sujeet?

01:33:50.760 --> 01:33:52.240
I got married in 2012.

01:33:52.320 --> 01:33:54.400
But I was, at that time, 31 years old.

01:33:54.480 --> 01:33:55.960
[Kishore giggles]

01:33:57.320 --> 01:33:58.720
Delhi.

01:33:59.558 --> 01:34:01.640
-My wife is from Haryana.
-[Nikhil] Hmm.

01:34:02.662 --> 01:34:04.920
Would you like to say something
about your personal life?

01:34:05.000 --> 01:34:08.240
Like just… You've seen so much in life,

01:34:08.320 --> 01:34:10.640
if you had to advise Vidit,

01:34:10.720 --> 01:34:13.690
who's new into this whole family,
marriage,

01:34:13.770 --> 01:34:16.040
doesn't have kids yet situation…

01:34:16.120 --> 01:34:18.920
-He also has decided never to have kids.
-[Sujeet] You also.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:20.100
No, no, I haven't.

01:34:20.180 --> 01:34:22.960
-At least not yet. I don't know.
-[all laughing]

01:34:23.040 --> 01:34:24.534
[Sujeet] He also needs some help.

01:34:24.614 --> 01:34:26.800
[Sujeet laughing]

01:34:26.880 --> 01:34:28.000
Lost cause.

01:34:33.840 --> 01:34:37.520
I personally believe, philosophically,
life is a series of events.

01:34:37.600 --> 01:34:43.280
And… you have to enjoy, relish,
cherish every event which comes in.

01:34:43.360 --> 01:34:46.607
Some events will be very heart-pleasing,

01:34:46.687 --> 01:34:50.160
and some events will be not so great.

01:34:50.240 --> 01:34:55.110
But I think the fun is
having all kinds of events.

01:34:55.190 --> 01:34:58.880
If you look at my life, we grew at 30%,

01:34:58.960 --> 01:35:01.320
life was unbelievable.

01:35:01.400 --> 01:35:04.040
It was up, up, up only.

01:35:04.120 --> 01:35:07.560
The lower side was much, much lower.

01:35:07.640 --> 01:35:08.640
This is like a tough question,

01:35:08.720 --> 01:35:10.640
I don't know
if I should even ask it or not.

01:35:12.062 --> 01:35:16.120
But in that 30% growth cycle,

01:35:16.200 --> 01:35:19.080
let's assume two or three things
went wrong, right?

01:35:20.480 --> 01:35:22.000
What do you think…

01:35:24.000 --> 01:35:26.268
I believe that in life
there are two buckets of things,

01:35:26.348 --> 01:35:28.280
one you can control,
another you can't control.

01:35:28.360 --> 01:35:29.520
For what you can't control,

01:35:29.600 --> 01:35:32.320
there's no point breaking your head
over it.

01:35:33.440 --> 01:35:37.036
Just as advice to us,
who are entrepreneurs,

01:35:37.116 --> 01:35:39.720
budding ones, and people around,

01:35:40.882 --> 01:35:45.360
what do you think went
wrong, what caused it,

01:35:45.440 --> 01:35:48.760
and if you had to do it over again,
what might you change?

01:35:50.800 --> 01:35:54.960
So, I'm a… As a personality,
I'm an impulsive person.

01:35:55.821 --> 01:36:00.360
So, what went wrong
is basically growing on debt,

01:36:00.440 --> 01:36:03.120
and not building a strong balance sheet.

01:36:04.381 --> 01:36:08.960
So, that is one thing which was apparent.

01:36:11.680 --> 01:36:14.440
My daughter just started
studying Shakespeare.

01:36:14.520 --> 01:36:16.000
So, the other day, some ten days back,

01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:18.000
she came out of the class
and she called me up,

01:36:18.080 --> 01:36:21.054
"Dad, I had one of the best days
of my life."

01:36:21.134 --> 01:36:25.800
I studied a concept of storytelling
called tragic flaw.

01:36:25.880 --> 01:36:28.440
So, every character which Shakespeare
built had a tragic flaw,

01:36:28.520 --> 01:36:32.120
and he used to highlight that flaw
in that character.

01:36:32.200 --> 01:36:35.800
Then I started looking at Ramayana,
Mahabharata, and everybody had a flaw.

01:36:35.880 --> 01:36:38.320
But flaw in India was
never highlighted as much.

01:36:38.400 --> 01:36:41.080
We were taught that everybody is perfect.

01:36:41.160 --> 01:36:42.932
So, everybody has a fatal flaw…

01:36:43.012 --> 01:36:45.720
I converted this tragic flaw
into a fatal flaw.

01:36:45.800 --> 01:36:48.560
And I started analyzing my fatal flaw.

01:36:48.640 --> 01:36:50.760
And I was able to discover a lot.

01:36:51.400 --> 01:36:53.080
So… [chuckles]

01:36:53.160 --> 01:36:54.860
And everybody has that flaw.

01:36:54.940 --> 01:36:57.840
And I believe every entrepreneur
has some flaw.

01:36:57.920 --> 01:37:00.840
Which, I think… which should be taught.

01:37:00.920 --> 01:37:03.480
And if somebody can work on it,

01:37:03.560 --> 01:37:06.800
they will make less number of mistakes
and will be more successful.

01:37:06.880 --> 01:37:09.560
So I have gone through flaws
and flaws and flaws.

01:37:10.520 --> 01:37:11.560
-So, all psycho…
-How do we discover

01:37:11.640 --> 01:37:12.920
that fatal flaw for us?

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:14.320
All psychology says this.

01:37:14.400 --> 01:37:18.240
If you go through Jung, Freud, Adler,

01:37:18.320 --> 01:37:20.920
like, much after Shakespeare's time,
obviously, but…

01:37:22.280 --> 01:37:24.760
We are all flawed, right?
We are all insecure,

01:37:24.840 --> 01:37:29.200
we are all not as altruistic

01:37:29.280 --> 01:37:32.680
like we might like to believe
at some level or we might like to portray.

01:37:32.760 --> 01:37:34.280
There is one true us,

01:37:34.360 --> 01:37:38.200
there is one persona of us
which we have created in our own mind,

01:37:38.280 --> 01:37:40.120
which we believe is not flawed.

01:37:40.200 --> 01:37:41.520
That persona.

01:37:41.600 --> 01:37:45.520
And we spend so much time and effort
defending that persona

01:37:45.600 --> 01:37:50.640
and denying our flaw
that it makes life more complicated

01:37:50.720 --> 01:37:53.000
even for us and for people around us.

01:37:53.080 --> 01:37:55.160
So, different people call it
different things.

01:37:55.240 --> 01:37:58.240
I think people like Jung and Adler
call it as "shadow".

01:37:59.480 --> 01:38:02.000
It is driven by many things,

01:38:02.080 --> 01:38:05.360
like, your childhood
has such a big impact on it.

01:38:05.440 --> 01:38:09.640
What you did between ages
three-four to eight-nine

01:38:09.720 --> 01:38:13.360
will have so much to do
with what your shadow is today.

01:38:13.440 --> 01:38:15.800
The financial condition of your parents,

01:38:15.880 --> 01:38:18.720
the relationship
between your mother and father,

01:38:18.800 --> 01:38:21.080
your relationship with your siblings,

01:38:21.160 --> 01:38:23.880
and also, innately,
how you're born as a person.

01:38:23.960 --> 01:38:30.400
So, every psychology book kinda tells you
that "Recognize your flaws."

01:38:30.480 --> 01:38:33.086
They, in fact, help you out
by doing some categorization.

01:38:33.166 --> 01:38:35.440
They say this could be
a certain kind of person,

01:38:35.520 --> 01:38:37.360
that could be a certain kind of person…

01:38:38.400 --> 01:38:40.960
But, Nikhil, this should be
taught to entrepreneurs.

01:38:41.040 --> 01:38:44.800
And you can find…
I have a very simple philosophy of life:

01:38:44.880 --> 01:38:49.640
Music has seven notes,
there are five primary colors,

01:38:49.720 --> 01:38:51.760
and there are nine recorded emotions
of human beings.

01:38:51.840 --> 01:38:53.520
Life is not so complex.

01:38:53.600 --> 01:38:55.200
So, if you look
at the flaws of entrepreneurs,

01:38:55.280 --> 01:38:57.440
I think it can be defined very well.

01:38:57.520 --> 01:38:59.920
And there are people like me…
Or many people like us

01:39:00.000 --> 01:39:03.680
who have made lot of mistakes,
and how can it be recorded and taught?

01:39:03.760 --> 01:39:05.800
[Nikhil] Especially for entrepreneurs…

01:39:05.880 --> 01:39:07.680
[in Hindi] …another problem
of ours is that…

01:39:08.880 --> 01:39:11.600
[in English] …we all gotten lucky
in the cycle of life.

01:39:11.680 --> 01:39:13.800
See, we are all sitting
here outside of [bleep]

01:39:13.880 --> 01:39:15.600
because we have gotten very lucky, right?

01:39:15.680 --> 01:39:18.120
I mean, Vidit is brilliant,
Sujeet is brilliant,

01:39:18.200 --> 01:39:19.520
you are brilliant,

01:39:19.600 --> 01:39:23.880
but, at some level, luck has played
a disproportionate part

01:39:23.960 --> 01:39:26.480
of how we've arrived to be
where we are today.

01:39:27.320 --> 01:39:30.600
But the problem, especially
in start-up crowds, is…

01:39:30.680 --> 01:39:34.240
Because somebody goes
from A to Z in two years,

01:39:34.320 --> 01:39:36.680
in three years, in five years,
in six years…

01:39:38.440 --> 01:39:41.440
you don't start to take
yourself so seriously,

01:39:41.520 --> 01:39:45.640
but the scale of everything
you're saying and doing is so much bigger

01:39:45.720 --> 01:39:48.161
that what you were saying
and doing five years ago,

01:39:48.241 --> 01:39:51.120
today will be looked at
through a completely different lens.

01:39:51.200 --> 01:39:55.400
So, even for that reason,
I think what he said is so true that

01:39:55.480 --> 01:39:59.640
we need to… Introspecting is
the hardest thing in life, maybe.

01:39:59.720 --> 01:40:02.560
And that's what I was going to ask,
like, how do you find these fatal flaws?

01:40:02.640 --> 01:40:04.480
I'm sure you now have some ways…

01:40:04.560 --> 01:40:06.440
After destruction, you can easily find it.

01:40:06.520 --> 01:40:09.120
-[loud laughter]
-Suddenly, you are open to it.

01:40:09.200 --> 01:40:12.360
I think we always created an organization
which allowed dissent,

01:40:12.440 --> 01:40:13.640
so that was not the challenge.

01:40:13.720 --> 01:40:17.560
Secondly, we never kept along
with ourselves our echo chambers.

01:40:17.640 --> 01:40:19.120
Never in our life.

01:40:20.360 --> 01:40:21.549
Everybody knows your weakness,

01:40:21.629 --> 01:40:23.720
everybody who is around you
will know your weakness.

01:40:23.800 --> 01:40:25.520
So you should ask them?

01:40:25.600 --> 01:40:27.720
No! They will never tell you
your weakness ever.

01:40:27.800 --> 01:40:29.920
-Yeah, yeah…
-So, how do we get it out, then?

01:40:30.000 --> 01:40:31.720 line:1%
[Kishore speaking in Hindi]

01:40:31.800 --> 01:40:32.800
The first thing to do is

01:40:32.880 --> 01:40:34.760
-normalize having flaws.
-[Kishore] Yeah.

01:40:34.840 --> 01:40:37.720
The problem with social media
and anonymity,

01:40:37.800 --> 01:40:41.240
what it has done is, people go out there
and say [bleep] about everybody.

01:40:42.120 --> 01:40:46.120
One should not care, but in many cases
you find yourself caring.

01:40:46.200 --> 01:40:49.360
But until we come to terms with the fact
that you are flawed,

01:40:49.440 --> 01:40:52.240
Sujeet is flawed, he is flawed,
I am flawed…

01:40:52.320 --> 01:40:56.880
until we realize that we each are,
and then we realize that we all are,

01:40:56.960 --> 01:41:00.800
I think people will be scared and shy
of coming out with their flaws.

01:41:00.880 --> 01:41:02.507
By the way, I have one disagreement
which is,

01:41:02.587 --> 01:41:04.720
I believe most entrepreneurs
are very paranoid also.

01:41:04.800 --> 01:41:07.320
So they believe something is
gonna go wrong at all points in time,

01:41:07.400 --> 01:41:08.640
and keep trying to figure it out.

01:41:08.720 --> 01:41:11.680
And that's why I feel if you tell them
that there's something wrong,

01:41:11.760 --> 01:41:14.554
where they go, "Yes, I can fix this,
and basically fixing this

01:41:14.634 --> 01:41:16.360
"would mean that something will grow."

01:41:16.440 --> 01:41:19.093
And, all of that happens,
but I genuinely feel people are…

01:41:19.173 --> 01:41:20.680
This is not what the flaw is…

01:41:20.760 --> 01:41:22.840
But people are paranoid.

01:41:22.920 --> 01:41:25.520
He's talking not about paranoia,
he's talking… I'll give you an example…

01:41:25.600 --> 01:41:26.880
[Kishore] Personality.

01:41:26.960 --> 01:41:28.600
He was saying… I'm saying that
people want to acknowledge

01:41:28.680 --> 01:41:29.680
that they could have flaws?

01:41:29.760 --> 01:41:31.280
I believe that is not true.

01:41:31.360 --> 01:41:33.200
I believe most people are paranoid.

01:41:33.280 --> 01:41:35.880
They just have a blind side
that no one exposes them to.

01:41:35.960 --> 01:41:37.440
I'll give you an example of a flaw.

01:41:37.520 --> 01:41:39.160
[Sujeet] I just wanted
to add to that point,

01:41:39.240 --> 01:41:41.480
when he was saying that there are people…

01:41:41.560 --> 01:41:45.680
As an entrepreneur, what you do is,
you focus too much on work.

01:41:45.760 --> 01:41:47.480
You circle starts getting shrunk.

01:41:47.560 --> 01:41:53.760
And then, you get surrounded by people
who might know but never want to share.

01:41:53.840 --> 01:41:58.120
Having those circles where people
can tell you… It's very hard.

01:41:58.200 --> 01:42:01.360
Who can tell you, speak with you frankly,

01:42:01.440 --> 01:42:03.672
or can give you
some kind of feedback, suggestion,

01:42:03.752 --> 01:42:05.120
and you should be open to that.

01:42:05.200 --> 01:42:08.640
Because if you give a reaction,
those channels are going to close.

01:42:08.720 --> 01:42:11.280
I think those feedback channels
are very important,

01:42:11.360 --> 01:42:12.920
but it's an investment.

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:15.880
It's an investment,
it automatically doesn't happen.

01:42:15.960 --> 01:42:19.280
But every entrepreneur,
I personally believe can easily learn it.

01:42:19.360 --> 01:42:20.800
They are open to ideas and thoughts.

01:42:20.880 --> 01:42:23.560
-No, sir, but it's very hard when…
-It's hard.

01:42:23.640 --> 01:42:26.440
…when it comes to talk about…

01:42:26.520 --> 01:42:29.520
Imagine, every corner, family member,
mother, father,

01:42:29.600 --> 01:42:32.360
everybody says that you are perfect.

01:42:32.440 --> 01:42:35.720 line:1%
[both speaking in Hindi]

01:42:40.720 --> 01:42:44.680
And your reaction, control,
that feedback will come again or not?

01:42:44.760 --> 01:42:49.280
If you give a different kind of reaction,
like you are, "Don't talk [bleep]."

01:42:50.200 --> 01:42:51.360
But our education also…

01:42:51.440 --> 01:42:54.400
Look at Rama.
Rama is the perfect human being.

01:42:54.480 --> 01:42:56.800
-[Vidit] Yeah, that's true.
-But he was also flawed.

01:42:56.880 --> 01:42:59.280
It was all about righteousness over…

01:42:59.360 --> 01:43:00.680
[Sujeet in Hindi] No,
but how do you identify it?

01:43:00.760 --> 01:43:02.520
[in English] I think the question was
how to control that.

01:43:02.600 --> 01:43:03.880
People are like, "We have to go…

01:43:03.960 --> 01:43:06.440
He understood the subject in one second.
He added up five things more…

01:43:06.520 --> 01:43:09.320
There will be people like him who will…

01:43:09.400 --> 01:43:11.080
Psychology is the best teacher.

01:43:11.160 --> 01:43:15.160
I will tell you personally, for me, right,
in the last three years,

01:43:15.240 --> 01:43:18.240
I have stopped reading
all books on finance, economy,

01:43:18.320 --> 01:43:20.320
which I used to spend time reading
while I was growing up.

01:43:20.400 --> 01:43:22.440
-[Sujeet] History and psychology.
-I just do history and psychology,

01:43:22.520 --> 01:43:23.880
I keep telling him.

01:43:23.960 --> 01:43:30.200
It's incredible how you will start
looking at yourself from a different lens.

01:43:30.280 --> 01:43:32.960
-Because we all spend…
-[Sujeet] And mythology.

01:43:33.040 --> 01:43:35.280
-[Kishore] Totally.
-[Sujeet] I'm adding.

01:43:35.360 --> 01:43:36.880
[Sujeet and Kishore chuckle softly]

01:43:36.960 --> 01:43:40.880
-We took mythology as a subject. Yeah.
-[Nikhil] Hmm. Okay.

01:43:40.960 --> 01:43:44.760
To digress again, ONDC.
Who is going to explain it?

01:43:44.840 --> 01:43:50.400
Is it life-changing for anybody
trying to build a product in e-commerce?

01:43:51.360 --> 01:43:53.440
What do you think will happen
to ONDC going forward?

01:43:53.520 --> 01:43:56.800
I think you, especially,
more than all people,

01:43:56.880 --> 01:44:01.920
because you have these
tiny mom-and-pop kind of stores

01:44:02.000 --> 01:44:05.520
who come and specifically sell on Meesho.
Can you explain?

01:44:06.920 --> 01:44:10.480
Yeah, so for people who don't know ONDC,
ONDC basically…

01:44:10.560 --> 01:44:12.200
We got a lesson today, little bit.

01:44:12.280 --> 01:44:14.400
-[Vidit chuckles]
-Before this meeting, when you were late,

01:44:14.480 --> 01:44:16.280
-we were watching that.
-Oh, great.

01:44:16.360 --> 01:44:21.320
Yes, so I'm saying,
it's a government initiative, trying to…

01:44:23.280 --> 01:44:26.740
onboard all kinds of small businesses
on a platform…

01:44:27.520 --> 01:44:32.760
And make all kinds of small businesses,
be it kirana, etc. basically come online,

01:44:32.840 --> 01:44:35.920
and really unbundle
the entire value chain. Right?

01:44:36.000 --> 01:44:39.960
I really believe the vision
and the mission there is quite powerful.

01:44:40.040 --> 01:44:42.790
Because we still don't find
any panwadi, etc.

01:44:42.870 --> 01:44:45.000
selling products online around you.

01:44:45.080 --> 01:44:48.440
India has about 60 million
small businesses…

01:44:48.520 --> 01:44:51.760
About a million, million and a half
only sell anything online.

01:44:51.840 --> 01:44:54.800
So, now you can say eventually
how many will do or don't do,

01:44:54.880 --> 01:44:56.200
I don't know.

01:44:56.280 --> 01:44:59.720
You look at South East Asia e-commerce,
they started four years after India,

01:44:59.800 --> 01:45:03.400
they got 15 million people
who sell online just in Indonesia.

01:45:03.480 --> 01:45:05.360
India is still million and a half.

01:45:05.440 --> 01:45:07.920
So, I think there's a problem
to be solved.

01:45:08.000 --> 01:45:10.640
I hope that ONDC is the answer.

01:45:10.720 --> 01:45:13.120
We have integrated with them,
hopefully that will solve,

01:45:13.200 --> 01:45:14.320
but still very early.

01:45:14.400 --> 01:45:18.240
In very simple words,
like, if you were to dumb it down for me…

01:45:18.320 --> 01:45:21.480 line:1%
If I am a seller who makes soaps, okay?

01:45:21.560 --> 01:45:23.560 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:45:23.640 --> 01:45:25.680
-[Vidit] Correct.
-After ONDC, how does my life change?

01:45:25.760 --> 01:45:27.812
So I think it's more interop…

01:45:27.892 --> 01:45:30.920
So, basically, they say that
it's like the UPI of e-commerce.

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:33.200
It is supposed to be that. Which is…

01:45:33.280 --> 01:45:36.360
You can upload your catalogue on any app,

01:45:36.440 --> 01:45:39.360
and it will start to appear
on all other apps

01:45:39.440 --> 01:45:41.440
which are integrated with ONDC.

01:45:41.520 --> 01:45:44.400 line:1%
So that's how it is supposed to be.
It's an interoperable e-commerce platform.

01:45:44.480 --> 01:45:46.360 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:45:46.440 --> 01:45:49.160
Tomorrow, when I put my soap on Meesho,

01:45:49.240 --> 01:45:51.920
will it automatically show up on Flipkart?

01:45:52.000 --> 01:45:53.920
It should. If everything is ONDC.

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:56.040
-That's the goal.
-[Sujeet] It's integrated.

01:45:56.120 --> 01:45:58.880
I have a very…
I want to ask you a question.

01:45:58.960 --> 01:46:01.400 line:1%
So, you all believe that…

01:46:01.480 --> 01:46:03.440 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:46:07.680 --> 01:46:09.000
No, I don't know…

01:46:09.080 --> 01:46:10.760
[in Hindi] Will the rate of consumption
increase?

01:46:10.840 --> 01:46:12.640
You see, supply follows demand.

01:46:12.720 --> 01:46:14.160
-The problem is this.
-I don't agree.

01:46:14.240 --> 01:46:15.880
Supply follows demand.

01:46:15.960 --> 01:46:16.960 line:1%
[conversing in Hindi]

01:46:26.960 --> 01:46:30.040 line:1%
I will give you an example,
because this happens so gradually.

01:46:30.120 --> 01:46:31.920 line:1%
[Kishore speaking in Hindi]

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:34.360
But this happens so gradually,
people don't understand.

01:46:34.440 --> 01:46:36.960
But if you look at pandemic,
where things happened very quickly, right?

01:46:37.040 --> 01:46:40.760
So, suddenly, for a year,
nothing was selling offline.

01:46:40.840 --> 01:46:42.960
And you meet any small business in India,

01:46:43.040 --> 01:46:44.241
people were like, "Oh, shit.

01:46:44.321 --> 01:46:46.320
"People used to come to me
and say sell online.

01:46:46.400 --> 01:46:51.040
"I did not do. Now I can't put food
on the table in my household."

01:46:51.120 --> 01:46:52.411
So, I'm saying, at that point in time,

01:46:52.491 --> 01:46:55.400
every small business in India
realized they want to be online.

01:46:55.480 --> 01:46:56.914
And to some extent,
by the way, informally,

01:46:56.994 --> 01:46:58.840
a lot of them are online
because they sell on WhatsApp.

01:46:58.920 --> 01:47:03.360
So you can say that panwadi also sends you
whatever you want on WhatsApp, right?

01:47:03.440 --> 01:47:07.080
Are they selling online?
Maybe yes. But still…

01:47:07.160 --> 01:47:09.750
like, quite hidden,
in some unstructured platforms,

01:47:09.830 --> 01:47:11.080
they haven't come online.

01:47:11.160 --> 01:47:13.680
And they can't get access
to a lot of demand

01:47:13.760 --> 01:47:15.560
that people who are selling online
are getting to.

01:47:15.640 --> 01:47:18.280
Like he was saying,
it is a digitization exercise.

01:47:18.360 --> 01:47:19.760
[Vidit in Hindi] Yes, so that will happen.

01:47:19.840 --> 01:47:21.546
[in English] But someone has to enable…

01:47:21.626 --> 01:47:24.480
And somehow, they've been lots
of roadblocks that haven't enabled it.

01:47:24.560 --> 01:47:26.240
Let's assume that it happens successfully.

01:47:26.320 --> 01:47:28.560 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:47:35.840 --> 01:47:39.480
Today, suddenly, the product shows up
in Amazon, Flipkart, everywhere.

01:47:41.200 --> 01:47:44.920
How does the use case
for an e-commerce platform change then?

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:50.760
Because then Amazon has less control over
what all products are listed under them.

01:47:52.720 --> 01:47:57.800
Yeah, and that's the… [sighs]
that's the unique thing about it…

01:47:57.880 --> 01:48:00.840
A lot of those design principles
haven't been thought of yet.

01:48:01.640 --> 01:48:03.720
Because everyone has
a different supply chain.

01:48:03.800 --> 01:48:07.520
If everything is available everywhere,
then who stands for what?

01:48:07.600 --> 01:48:09.760
What does a brand stand for?

01:48:09.840 --> 01:48:11.556
Because everyone uses
the same supply chain

01:48:11.636 --> 01:48:13.720
so the product will come in
the same amount of time.

01:48:13.800 --> 01:48:15.200
If everything comes
in the same amount of time,

01:48:15.280 --> 01:48:17.920
then how will Amazon build
a different identity than anyone else?

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:20.314
The problem is no one
has thought about it,

01:48:20.394 --> 01:48:22.160
even people who have designed it.

01:48:22.240 --> 01:48:24.440 line:1%
It's still very early.

01:48:25.480 --> 01:48:27.920
I don't know what will happen there.

01:48:28.000 --> 01:48:29.920
That's a fair explanation.

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:32.880
-[Sujeet] It's an idea.
-Because if everyone is the same,

01:48:32.960 --> 01:48:34.609
then how do people
stand for different things

01:48:34.689 --> 01:48:36.000
and why will you have multiple apps?

01:48:36.080 --> 01:48:38.720
-Then who will really do it?
-[Sujeet] Who is going to benefit?

01:48:38.800 --> 01:48:40.760
Which is a big problem,
payments are same on every app.

01:48:40.840 --> 01:48:45.200
It's not that if I do payment…
with one app to the other,

01:48:45.280 --> 01:48:46.880
that they stand for different things.

01:48:46.960 --> 01:48:50.840
Like, payments is commoditized…
one simple thing. Products are not.

01:48:50.920 --> 01:48:55.120
Two different stores you go to
cannot be exactly the same.

01:48:55.200 --> 01:48:57.415
They stand for different things,
what they merchandise,

01:48:57.495 --> 01:48:59.560
what they talk about,
what their marketing line is,

01:48:59.640 --> 01:49:00.880
they are very different things.

01:49:00.960 --> 01:49:04.880
So, if you try to commoditize
storefronts or market places,

01:49:04.960 --> 01:49:06.920
it's never been done before.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:09.360
So, how does it really come to life?
No one knows.

01:49:09.440 --> 01:49:11.520
So I don't have a good answer
to this question.

01:49:12.640 --> 01:49:14.520
Even the government is not very clear,

01:49:14.600 --> 01:49:17.440
they are trying,
they are bringing the people together…

01:49:17.520 --> 01:49:21.120
But let's see,
everybody has their own hidden agenda.

01:49:22.920 --> 01:49:27.200
In India, investing into e-commerce,
there aren't many opportunities.

01:49:27.280 --> 01:49:29.920
Flipkart is owned by Walmart,
they are not listed here.

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:33.040
One can argue you can buy
Walmart shares in America,

01:49:33.120 --> 01:49:36.120
but that would diversify you too much.

01:49:36.200 --> 01:49:40.240 line:1%
The only option I would
say arguably is Nykaa…

01:49:41.126 --> 01:49:42.326 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:49:44.720 --> 01:49:46.120
…in the listed space.

01:49:46.920 --> 01:49:49.320
What do you guys think of Nykaa,

01:49:49.400 --> 01:49:51.640
the business model of Nykaa?

01:49:51.720 --> 01:49:55.560
And what do you think
will happen to Nykaa going forward?

01:49:55.640 --> 01:49:57.280
I know they are your competition, but…

01:49:57.361 --> 01:50:00.640
No, we're not, by the way.
I believe it's a very different business.

01:50:00.720 --> 01:50:02.640
Like, we are a platform, they're a brand.

01:50:02.720 --> 01:50:05.120
-So, I think it's…
-Are they a brand? Because they're not…

01:50:05.200 --> 01:50:06.520
They're distributing third-party products.

01:50:06.600 --> 01:50:07.920
[Kishore] Yeah,
but still they are a brand.

01:50:08.000 --> 01:50:09.320
[Sujeet] They're a brand.

01:50:09.400 --> 01:50:11.418
Well, look at Amazon as a brand.

01:50:11.480 --> 01:50:15.440
It's a brand, Flipkart is a brand.
Nykaa is a brand, Meesho is also a brand.

01:50:15.520 --> 01:50:16.880
They've worked on building the brand, so…

01:50:16.960 --> 01:50:20.360
Yeah, but my…
Still, my thing was, like, they…

01:50:21.960 --> 01:50:23.519
A lot of what they do offline-online,

01:50:23.599 --> 01:50:26.920
the kind of products they sell,
a lot of products are exclusive.

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:28.000
So, basically…

01:50:28.080 --> 01:50:30.440
-But vast majority of what they sell…
-[Vidit] Yes.

01:50:30.520 --> 01:50:34.200
…let's say they do 4,000 crores
of business a year.

01:50:34.280 --> 01:50:36.280
Let's say 5% margin kind of business.

01:50:37.080 --> 01:50:40.440
Operating margin or net margin, 5%.

01:50:40.520 --> 01:50:44.000
But… most of what they sell
is third-party products

01:50:44.080 --> 01:50:45.200
that they are distributing.

01:50:47.480 --> 01:50:50.207
So, that's why I think my understanding
of the business could also be limited,

01:50:50.287 --> 01:50:52.515
but from what I've seen,
how they've approached it,

01:50:52.595 --> 01:50:55.158
a lot of that business has been built by

01:50:55.238 --> 01:50:57.680
getting supply
that you won't get everywhere, right?

01:50:57.760 --> 01:51:00.057
So they've been much more focused
on going very deep

01:51:00.137 --> 01:51:02.760
into that particular category
and making it happen.

01:51:02.840 --> 01:51:03.840
If, by the way,

01:51:03.920 --> 01:51:06.560
you can get the same supply
that you have in Nykaa,

01:51:06.640 --> 01:51:09.080
you can get on Amazon
and they'll ship, like, the next day,

01:51:09.160 --> 01:51:12.000
why won't you buy from there?
And it should not happen, right?

01:51:12.080 --> 01:51:14.160
-But it does not.
-If somebody is buying,

01:51:14.240 --> 01:51:18.869
are they betting into the story of India 2
growing significantly

01:51:18.949 --> 01:51:20.280
and India 1 growing as well?

01:51:21.280 --> 01:51:25.520
But I… But a woman child is getting, uh,

01:51:25.600 --> 01:51:28.400
getting into beauty even in India 2.

01:51:29.600 --> 01:51:31.080
In a very significant way.

01:51:31.760 --> 01:51:34.214
So, there is some budget of the family
going into beauty.

01:51:34.294 --> 01:51:36.200
Beauty, as a category,
is also growing significantly.

01:51:36.280 --> 01:51:37.280
Very fast.

01:51:37.360 --> 01:51:38.680
That's actually
a very interesting question.

01:51:38.760 --> 01:51:41.480
But India 2, by the way, in terms
of beauty, ends up being lipstick,

01:51:41.560 --> 01:51:42.880
nail polish, or foundation.

01:51:42.960 --> 01:51:46.040
But that's also a three category…
Three SKUs, not small.

01:51:46.120 --> 01:51:48.320
-Yeah, but it's very…
-…started three, four, five….

01:51:48.400 --> 01:51:51.160
How does one evaluate
something like Nykaa?

01:51:52.440 --> 01:51:53.920
How does one benchmark?

01:51:54.000 --> 01:51:56.120
I'm asking because you both
are in e-commerce.

01:51:56.200 --> 01:51:58.520
You've had Flipkart, Udaan.
You have Meesho.

01:51:59.161 --> 01:52:02.200
If I'm an investor trying to figure out
I should invest in the company…

01:52:02.280 --> 01:52:05.560
Like, I think Falguni
is an exceptional entrepreneur.

01:52:05.640 --> 01:52:08.223
I know her, and I think

01:52:08.303 --> 01:52:11.680
if anybody can pull it off,
it's possibly or likely her.

01:52:12.364 --> 01:52:15.456
She's had an exceptional past
and great management

01:52:15.536 --> 01:52:17.000
and all of those things.

01:52:17.560 --> 01:52:19.520
But the broader question is…

01:52:20.960 --> 01:52:25.520
how big is the e-commerce pie in India,
and are we betting

01:52:26.440 --> 01:52:29.388
based on the valuations
of whatever I mentioned?

01:52:29.468 --> 01:52:32.932
Are we betting that India 1 and 2
will grow to X%

01:52:33.012 --> 01:52:35.547
in the next five years or ten years?

01:52:35.627 --> 01:52:37.240
Is that the bet we are making?

01:52:37.320 --> 01:52:39.590
Yeah, I've… I don't know the answer
to that question,

01:52:39.670 --> 01:52:40.720
and I won't even attempt,

01:52:40.800 --> 01:52:44.504
but what I know is I don't think
that company is a good representation

01:52:44.584 --> 01:52:45.600
of India e-commerce,

01:52:45.680 --> 01:52:47.999
because it's very narrow in a category

01:52:48.079 --> 01:52:50.376
and very narrow
in terms of the customer base they serve.

01:52:50.456 --> 01:52:53.440
Their average order value, if I remember,
was some 1,500… 1,800…

01:52:53.520 --> 01:52:54.920
2,000 something like that.

01:52:55.000 --> 01:52:58.357
-[Kishore] But it's not less.
-It's quite high, it's very high.

01:52:58.437 --> 01:53:00.288
So, my point is, it's super high.

01:53:00.368 --> 01:53:04.033
So, the segment exposure
and category exposure

01:53:04.113 --> 01:53:05.760
cannot be representational
of the e-commerce market.

01:53:05.840 --> 01:53:06.840
That's what I believe.

01:53:06.920 --> 01:53:08.200
-Okay, let's talk about Meesho.
-Yes.

01:53:08.280 --> 01:53:12.040
Let's make it more interesting.
What is your valuation today?

01:53:12.720 --> 01:53:14.440
Valuation today? Our valuation?

01:53:14.520 --> 01:53:16.616
This was the last round,
about five billion.

01:53:16.696 --> 01:53:19.600
Okay. And, uh, give us some metrics,
like, some numbers

01:53:19.680 --> 01:53:21.040
and whatever is publicly available.

01:53:21.120 --> 01:53:23.330
Yeah, so I'm saying
we have about 14 crore people

01:53:23.410 --> 01:53:24.611
who buy from us every year,

01:53:24.691 --> 01:53:26.843
about a million small businesses.

01:53:26.923 --> 01:53:29.880
Um, in the last one year,
we did about one billion orders,

01:53:29.960 --> 01:53:31.760
which is, what? 100 crores?

01:53:31.840 --> 01:53:34.640
So, about 100 crore orders
in the last 12 months.

01:53:34.720 --> 01:53:38.160
Those are insane numbers, by the way.
Right? 14 crore people buying.

01:53:38.240 --> 01:53:39.996
Yeah, and, by the way, we sell across.

01:53:40.076 --> 01:53:42.908
So, horizontal platform,
people come and sell anything they want.

01:53:42.988 --> 01:53:46.436
So, about half is apparel,
and half is non-apparel,

01:53:46.516 --> 01:53:51.320
and that includes kids, beauty,
personal care, your electronics.

01:53:51.400 --> 01:53:52.800
So, what is the GMV…

01:53:53.560 --> 01:53:55.720
Like, the gross sales that happen on…

01:53:55.800 --> 01:53:59.040
Yeah, so about, like,
last 2020 calendar year,

01:53:59.120 --> 01:54:02.080
was about four and a half,
quarter to five billion.

01:54:02.160 --> 01:54:03.160
Um…

01:54:03.800 --> 01:54:08.560
So… which is last year.
And what is the margin on the top-level?

01:54:08.640 --> 01:54:10.344
Out of this 5 billion you sell,
on average,

01:54:10.424 --> 01:54:11.520
how much margin do you have?

01:54:11.600 --> 01:54:12.840 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:54:14.840 --> 01:54:17.920
Why do you want to open my PnL
in front of me here right now?

01:54:18.000 --> 01:54:19.048
Right, right.

01:54:19.128 --> 01:54:20.368 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:54:22.120 --> 01:54:24.025
Dealing with that kind of customers.

01:54:24.120 --> 01:54:25.880 line:1%
[Nikhil speaking in Hindi]

01:54:25.960 --> 01:54:28.560 line:1%
320. I'm saying
that's the problem we have to solve.

01:54:28.640 --> 01:54:30.120 line:1%
[Kishore] That's the biggest problem.

01:54:30.200 --> 01:54:32.040
-[Vidit] Correct.
-What would that be for Flipkart?

01:54:33.200 --> 01:54:36.640
[Vidit] Would be much higher.
Again, 1,200, 1,300. Maybe higher.

01:54:36.720 --> 01:54:39.027
Because there,
the electronics, mobile phones

01:54:39.107 --> 01:54:41.040
takes the average order value quite high.

01:54:41.100 --> 01:54:44.360
Plus, they have Myntra,
theirs will be very high.

01:54:45.280 --> 01:54:48.240
We didn't answer the Nykaa thing.

01:54:48.320 --> 01:54:50.640
What are the final thoughts
on a company like Nykaa?

01:54:51.562 --> 01:54:53.560
Because I don't have
another listed player in mind.

01:54:53.640 --> 01:54:55.042
What's your interest?

01:54:56.042 --> 01:54:58.843
No, I said… I said
I don't know about the company,

01:54:58.923 --> 01:55:01.840
but I don't believe
it represents India e-commerce.

01:55:01.920 --> 01:55:06.080
That's okay. I believe it's picked up
the right category at the right time.

01:55:06.960 --> 01:55:12.040
And secondly, they build their own
strength of the content to commerce.

01:55:12.120 --> 01:55:14.360
I think it was a very interesting way
they built it.

01:55:16.280 --> 01:55:18.240
There are negatives that, uh…

01:55:19.560 --> 01:55:21.960
They have attracted attention
and too many players are coming in.

01:55:23.760 --> 01:55:24.880
Uh…

01:55:24.960 --> 01:55:30.513
They need to build their own brand
in the ecosystem,

01:55:30.593 --> 01:55:31.832
which they might be doing.

01:55:31.912 --> 01:55:34.920
They went into too many things now.
They went into B2B.

01:55:35.720 --> 01:55:37.840
But I was surprised that even, uh, the…

01:55:37.920 --> 01:55:42.000
I never thought beauty and fashion
as a adjacency will work as much,

01:55:42.080 --> 01:55:45.320
-but Nykaa is not doing bad on fashion.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:55:45.400 --> 01:55:47.560
They just launched that Alo Yoga, no?

01:55:48.720 --> 01:55:52.280
They are distributors, right?
Killing it, that brand, abroad.

01:55:52.360 --> 01:55:55.520
It's doing reasonably quite okay.

01:55:56.320 --> 01:56:00.400
If they are able to build adjacencies,
it becomes an interesting story.

01:56:01.320 --> 01:56:05.423
[Sujeet] I think one thing
you have to give it to… Nykaa,

01:56:05.503 --> 01:56:08.648
they have built the business
with the discipline, unit economy,

01:56:08.728 --> 01:56:10.480
so that they have gone to market

01:56:10.560 --> 01:56:14.640
and definitely the market believes
in their, uh, in their IPO.

01:56:14.720 --> 01:56:18.840
Like, everybody…
They're still holding up very high

01:56:18.920 --> 01:56:21.040
given the comparison to their revenue.

01:56:21.960 --> 01:56:25.400
I think only problem is
how to expand their time.

01:56:26.304 --> 01:56:27.920
Is it the similar…

01:56:28.000 --> 01:56:32.040
Because the category they are in,
it's already niche.

01:56:33.680 --> 01:56:36.360
And build… As a commerce…
So, it's very hard to say that

01:56:36.440 --> 01:56:38.677
it's a full-fledged e-commerce.

01:56:38.757 --> 01:56:41.240
I will not call it as
a platformized e-commerce,

01:56:41.320 --> 01:56:42.320
it's a vertical.

01:56:43.000 --> 01:56:46.520
Definitely, they are building
other verticals also, adjacency, but…

01:56:47.240 --> 01:56:49.040
it's a difficult journey. Let's see.

01:56:49.120 --> 01:56:50.880
If I had to, like, figure out…

01:56:50.960 --> 01:56:53.480
Let's say I have 100 rupees to invest,

01:56:54.232 --> 01:56:56.000
and I want to invest in e-commerce…

01:56:56.080 --> 01:56:57.318 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:57:00.600 --> 01:57:03.960
Because even now more and more of
what's gonna come in the public markets,

01:57:04.040 --> 01:57:06.832
what people say is, there is Nykaa…

01:57:06.912 --> 01:57:10.072
Now FirstCry is someone
who's saying, "We'll go public."

01:57:10.152 --> 01:57:11.360
Will be very similar…

01:57:12.200 --> 01:57:14.926
Like, one sector, certain…

01:57:15.006 --> 01:57:18.324
You think that'll be the key curation
with ONDC, with many platforms?

01:57:18.404 --> 01:57:19.719
No, no, I think that's why
what's happening is,

01:57:19.799 --> 01:57:23.920
these value… value-adding brands
are going online, platforms will come.

01:57:24.000 --> 01:57:27.440
And I don't know, both the other platform,
Walmart and Amazon,

01:57:27.520 --> 01:57:29.320
they will list in India? Unlikely.

01:57:29.400 --> 01:57:31.720
So, hopefully, we will do it
at some point in time.

01:57:31.800 --> 01:57:32.800
[Nikhil] Right.

01:57:32.880 --> 01:57:35.055
But I feel like that
the e-commerce exposure

01:57:35.135 --> 01:57:36.601
that you keep referring to,

01:57:36.681 --> 01:57:39.600
unless you take parts
of all of them and say,

01:57:39.680 --> 01:57:42.000
"We did everything,
at least we'll have some exposure."

01:57:42.080 --> 01:57:43.480
Otherwise, all of them are very…

01:57:43.560 --> 01:57:45.840
There is Jio. They have a big aspiration.

01:57:47.139 --> 01:57:48.120 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:57:50.560 --> 01:57:55.000
Should I be in e-commerce,
or is the market too saturated?

01:57:55.080 --> 01:57:56.421
[Sujeet] As a career?

01:57:56.501 --> 01:57:58.280
-[Vidit] To start a platform?
-As a career.

01:57:58.360 --> 01:58:00.320
[Vidit] To start a platform
or to be a merchant?

01:58:00.400 --> 01:58:02.680
…e-commerce. There's no other option
but to be a part of it.

01:58:02.760 --> 01:58:04.840
Yeah, I mean, being part of e-commerce…

01:58:04.920 --> 01:58:07.614
The only way is
not to be a platform, right?

01:58:07.694 --> 01:58:10.480
Like, now, all the D2C brands
are part of e-commerce.

01:58:10.560 --> 01:58:11.760
[Kishore] Yeah, they're all e-commerce.

01:58:11.840 --> 01:58:13.800
And everyone… So the beautiful thing
that has happened

01:58:13.880 --> 01:58:15.438
because of the e-commerce platforms is

01:58:15.518 --> 01:58:18.720
now personalization and localization
that can happen…

01:58:19.400 --> 01:58:21.240
Like, it was not possible.

01:58:21.320 --> 01:58:23.147
So now, people are, like,
finding very niche

01:58:23.227 --> 01:58:24.360
and basically serving them.

01:58:24.440 --> 01:58:28.280
So you only get discovered
with a particular search term,

01:58:28.360 --> 01:58:29.960
and people buy you again and again.

01:58:30.040 --> 01:58:33.040
I'm saying lots of these micro D2C brands
are possible. So, I'm saying…

01:58:34.040 --> 01:58:35.600
being part of e-commerce,

01:58:35.680 --> 01:58:37.840
everything that you do around
selling digital products

01:58:37.920 --> 01:58:39.103
is being part of e-commerce,

01:58:39.183 --> 01:58:41.960
and I believe it will only accelerate,
because there's no other way anymore.

01:58:42.040 --> 01:58:44.200 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

01:58:44.280 --> 01:58:45.960
Like, especially us three
living in Bangalore,

01:58:46.040 --> 01:58:47.480
we're all from this…

01:58:48.160 --> 01:58:52.360
We're all products of a startup bubble
which started last decade.

01:58:52.440 --> 01:58:56.560
And I think to be fair, like,
we were talking about knowing your flaws.

01:58:56.640 --> 01:58:58.461
I think we're cognizant to the fact

01:58:58.541 --> 01:59:00.840
that we are by-products
of a startup bubble.

01:59:02.400 --> 01:59:06.345
What happens to e-commerce

01:59:06.425 --> 01:59:12.080
once the deep discounting in a way
or the marketing money

01:59:12.160 --> 01:59:18.360
which was funded by
cheap cost of capital abroad goes away?

01:59:18.440 --> 01:59:20.218
Like, how do things change?

01:59:20.298 --> 01:59:23.720
Let's say there is no funding available

01:59:23.800 --> 01:59:29.360
for growth for Indian e-commerce companies
in the next three years,

01:59:29.440 --> 01:59:32.040
and they have to survive
with the money they have left.

01:59:33.360 --> 01:59:34.920
How does each one change?

01:59:35.899 --> 01:59:38.120
In my mind,
it's a very hypothetical question.

01:59:39.040 --> 01:59:41.920
But I think… Look…

01:59:43.369 --> 01:59:46.517
when you are building a business,
you know that this much money you need.

01:59:46.597 --> 01:59:48.280
Say plus-minus, we can say that.

01:59:48.880 --> 01:59:52.920
I think only you can say that,
"Hey, growth is the right metrics."

01:59:53.920 --> 01:59:54.920
If you are growing…

01:59:55.640 --> 01:59:57.425
then investing money even though,

01:59:57.505 --> 01:59:59.847
let's say profitability comes after,
let's say, four or five years…

01:59:59.927 --> 02:00:03.400
-I don't agree, I don't…
-Hear me out, hear me out. I understand.

02:00:05.321 --> 02:00:10.640
But if you are with those
unit… in your boundaries,

02:00:10.720 --> 02:00:13.080
you are capturing the market share
and growing.

02:00:14.240 --> 02:00:18.440
I think I am that kind of student
where I'll support that.

02:00:18.520 --> 02:00:22.320
But burning money and hurting the company…

02:00:23.880 --> 02:00:25.840
like you burn money, you get the GMV.

02:00:25.920 --> 02:00:27.320
-See, but see…
-But your…

02:00:27.400 --> 02:00:30.360
unit economics not holding,
you should not do that.

02:00:30.440 --> 02:00:31.840
-But you're making…
-You'll kill your company.

02:00:31.920 --> 02:00:34.476
But you are also making an assumption
that this tap is open

02:00:34.556 --> 02:00:36.960
where you continue
to get money to burn money.

02:00:37.040 --> 02:00:39.960
By the way, unit economics, I also feel…

02:00:40.040 --> 02:00:42.600
Like why unit economics, why not EBITDA?

02:00:42.680 --> 02:00:44.200
I'll tell you why.

02:00:44.280 --> 02:00:46.320
And it's a great thing. It's a…

02:00:46.400 --> 02:00:48.560
Of course, EBITDA.
Everybody is aiming for EBITDA.

02:00:48.640 --> 02:00:49.800
I am not contesting that.

02:00:49.880 --> 02:00:52.080
So, I am saying that
if that has to be positive,

02:00:52.160 --> 02:00:53.440
ideally, you should make money.

02:00:53.520 --> 02:00:54.791
In some cohorts, let's say…

02:00:54.871 --> 02:00:58.520
Growth is an important matrix also.

02:00:58.600 --> 02:00:59.600
That's the problem.

02:01:00.560 --> 02:01:03.080
I've been a growth story in a way,

02:01:03.160 --> 02:01:05.040
and I don't think that holds true.

02:01:06.280 --> 02:01:08.960
Because I'll tell you why,
I'll explain to you why.

02:01:09.040 --> 02:01:12.640
After a point, the growth
comes at an extraordinary cost.

02:01:14.560 --> 02:01:16.360 line:1%
And that's what I am saying,
that we should not do that

02:01:16.440 --> 02:01:17.640 line:1%
if it is coming at an extraordinary cost.

02:01:18.400 --> 02:01:19.640 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

02:01:20.960 --> 02:01:22.680
[In English] You'll be so lost
in that journey of growth

02:01:22.760 --> 02:01:24.160
that you want it at any cost.

02:01:24.240 --> 02:01:26.360
You want to be the leader
in the category and the space

02:01:26.440 --> 02:01:28.560
-which you belong to.
-I think that is so true.

02:01:28.640 --> 02:01:30.600
-Many, many…
-By the way, I believe…

02:01:30.680 --> 02:01:32.800
So, my opinion is
there are multiple things.

02:01:32.880 --> 02:01:35.560
They are one stage of the business,
especially in e-commerce.

02:01:35.640 --> 02:01:38.080
You need to cross
a critical mass of scale.

02:01:38.160 --> 02:01:39.200
Yeah, that growth is required.

02:01:39.280 --> 02:01:40.937
And unless you get there,

02:01:41.017 --> 02:01:45.280
if you try to become profitable too soon,
you get into a negative spiral.

02:01:45.360 --> 02:01:46.600
It's okay, both ways.

02:01:46.680 --> 02:01:49.200
Because people take the same lesson,
apply across stages.

02:01:49.280 --> 02:01:50.600
-I don't believe it works.
-So, I… I have a…

02:01:50.680 --> 02:01:52.000
So you have to get to critical mass,

02:01:52.080 --> 02:01:54.040
but after that, I believe
you need to be profitable.

02:01:54.120 --> 02:01:55.320
-Yeah, of course, I'm not…
-Right?

02:01:55.400 --> 02:01:57.160
So, our goal is, I think
by the end of this year,

02:01:57.240 --> 02:01:59.000
we'll become profitable because…

02:01:59.080 --> 02:02:00.800 line:1%
[in Hindi] If not now, then when?

02:02:00.880 --> 02:02:02.360
[in English] Right?
You have five billion in sales,

02:02:02.440 --> 02:02:04.520
now you gotta make sure that
business becomes profitable.

02:02:04.600 --> 02:02:06.640
But if I tried to do it four years ago,

02:02:06.720 --> 02:02:09.000
I would made a… like a big blunder.

02:02:09.080 --> 02:02:10.200
[Kishore] Fair enough.

02:02:10.280 --> 02:02:12.080
So, Nikhil, I have a very interesting take
on technology.

02:02:12.160 --> 02:02:15.080
So I always believe that technology does
three or four things,

02:02:15.160 --> 02:02:18.640
which are different from the traditional
or the old economy.

02:02:18.720 --> 02:02:23.200
One, it reduces space, reduces time,
and create social interactions.

02:02:23.920 --> 02:02:26.400
And like in fashion business,

02:02:26.480 --> 02:02:28.640
on digital commerce,
you can do ten stock turns.

02:02:28.720 --> 02:02:31.400
Wherein in physical, you can't do
more than three, three and a half.

02:02:31.480 --> 02:02:33.240
You can work with less number of people.

02:02:33.320 --> 02:02:35.600
You can institutionalize
a lot of processes.

02:02:36.240 --> 02:02:39.080
And then, social interaction
is something, digitally,

02:02:39.160 --> 02:02:42.000
you can build a lot and acquire customers

02:02:42.080 --> 02:02:44.320
at a much lower cost than what physical…

02:02:44.400 --> 02:02:47.880
Because in physical, the old economy
used to advertise for everybody.

02:02:47.960 --> 02:02:50.120
Here you can target, you can do a lot.

02:02:50.200 --> 02:02:51.480
So, it has a lot of advantages.

02:02:51.560 --> 02:02:53.600
Anybody who'll take advantages
of all these things

02:02:53.680 --> 02:02:54.760
is going to be the winner.

02:02:54.840 --> 02:02:56.600
And constraint can create companies.

02:02:56.680 --> 02:02:58.600
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Of course, I…

02:02:58.680 --> 02:03:00.200
I… from…

02:03:00.280 --> 02:03:04.040
And lastly, I also believe that
unless you are getting into…

02:03:04.120 --> 02:03:06.360
Unless you don't have X amount
of value addition done,

02:03:06.440 --> 02:03:07.960
you are not in a business only.

02:03:08.560 --> 02:03:09.560
[Sujeet] Yes, yes.

02:03:10.960 --> 02:03:13.720
But in e-commerce also, I can see a…

02:03:13.800 --> 02:03:15.560
A scaled business,
these are scaled businesses.

02:03:15.640 --> 02:03:18.240
And that's why I was not able
to answer on the Nykaa,

02:03:18.320 --> 02:03:21.560
because I was not imagining
how or where their scale will come from.

02:03:21.640 --> 02:03:22.760
Because you know, supply chain,

02:03:22.840 --> 02:03:26.040
the same thing goes on,
because those are the principles

02:03:26.120 --> 02:03:29.360
where more and more scale,
you can reduce the cost.

02:03:30.520 --> 02:03:32.800
I think building those capabilities

02:03:32.880 --> 02:03:37.080
where sourcing is a big thing
in e-commerce.

02:03:37.160 --> 02:03:39.440
Let's say, and…

02:03:39.520 --> 02:03:41.080
But retailing is sourcing.

02:03:41.160 --> 02:03:43.720
-No, but sourcing has…
-Sourcing as in…

02:03:43.800 --> 02:03:45.280
If I'll crack sourcing…

02:03:46.120 --> 02:03:47.120
And definitely, I'm not…

02:03:47.200 --> 02:03:50.240
I'm talking about the going and having…

02:03:50.320 --> 02:03:54.600
doing that math on sourcing
rather than buying,

02:03:55.160 --> 02:03:56.472
keeping that inventory,

02:03:56.552 --> 02:03:59.040
and then distributing
and saving the money,

02:03:59.120 --> 02:04:00.960
I think that's a lose match.

02:04:01.040 --> 02:04:03.720
And it will only come on certain scales

02:04:03.800 --> 02:04:06.200
when you are involved
on the production side of it.

02:04:06.280 --> 02:04:12.040
Interesting. Any final words for anybody
looking to get involved in e-commerce?

02:04:13.160 --> 02:04:14.480
Final thoughts.

02:04:14.560 --> 02:04:16.560 line:1%
[speaking in Hindi]

02:04:22.760 --> 02:04:25.320
So, when I look at D2C brands, it was…

02:04:25.400 --> 02:04:26.840
Uh, D2C brands are something like,

02:04:26.920 --> 02:04:29.800
uh, you're living in a neighborhood
and you opened a shop.

02:04:30.600 --> 02:04:32.030
And you start from there,

02:04:32.110 --> 02:04:34.600
and from there you grow
and open to a much…

02:04:34.680 --> 02:04:37.600
It allows you to open
to a much, much larger audience.

02:04:37.680 --> 02:04:39.680
So, that's the way forward.

02:04:39.760 --> 02:04:42.880
You can't now go and open a shop
below your building.

02:04:42.960 --> 02:04:44.640
It's great to get into digital commerce,

02:04:44.720 --> 02:04:47.200
and if you're lucky and if you do well,

02:04:47.280 --> 02:04:50.360
if you're passionate, I think
it's a great business to be in.

02:04:52.320 --> 02:04:54.240
No, I believe there's no other way, right?

02:04:54.320 --> 02:04:57.760
So, I believe, as I think
we started in the beginning,

02:04:57.840 --> 02:05:01.160
the definition between e-commerce,
commerce, offline commerce

02:05:01.240 --> 02:05:03.040
are getting blurred more and more.

02:05:03.120 --> 02:05:05.200
So, if you wanna do anything in commerce,

02:05:05.280 --> 02:05:08.920
you have to basically figure out
how to make e-commerce work.

02:05:09.600 --> 02:05:12.080
This holds true for anyone
who's starting a business today.

02:05:12.680 --> 02:05:16.400
So, I think if you wanna create value,
I think you will become a part of this.

02:05:16.480 --> 02:05:18.640
So, I think instead of asking,
"Should I become part of this,"

02:05:18.720 --> 02:05:22.240
question is, "What do I need to do
to really become successful at this?"

02:05:23.160 --> 02:05:24.680
And I believe that will happen.

02:05:25.360 --> 02:05:28.920
Like social, figuring out influencers,
figuring out everything else,

02:05:29.000 --> 02:05:30.800
figuring out marketplaces.

02:05:32.040 --> 02:05:34.640
I think, on contrary,
this has integrated them,

02:05:35.440 --> 02:05:37.160
because you get the same product,
same thing.

02:05:37.240 --> 02:05:40.640
Earlier, when people define that
when offline,

02:05:40.720 --> 02:05:42.760
you'll get something in Delhi or in Mumbai

02:05:42.840 --> 02:05:45.760
or in big cities,
you'll not get in tier-2 or in…

02:05:45.840 --> 02:05:48.920
Now, e-commerce made it…
every product is available everywhere.

02:05:49.000 --> 02:05:51.120
We all agreed that's become
a very relevant part, right?

02:05:51.200 --> 02:05:52.200
-Figuring out…
-Very big.

02:05:52.280 --> 02:05:54.360
-Yeah.
-…to sell anything.

02:05:54.440 --> 02:05:55.440
Hmm.

02:05:56.760 --> 02:05:59.440
So, I think if you are doing commerce,
online will happen for sure.

02:05:59.520 --> 02:06:02.760
Some people will do hybrid as well,
but I'm also seeing…

02:06:03.600 --> 02:06:08.200
So, for example, 40% of sellers on Meesho
are online-only sellers.

02:06:08.280 --> 02:06:10.200
They don't sell anywhere else.
So, they have basic…

02:06:10.280 --> 02:06:12.480
They became entrepreneurs
for the first time,

02:06:12.560 --> 02:06:14.840
because they figured out,
"Hey, I can go on this platform.

02:06:14.920 --> 02:06:19.680
"I figure… I know how to merchandize well,
how to price well,

02:06:19.760 --> 02:06:22.480
"how to figure out what trends work
on this marketplace and so on."

02:06:23.440 --> 02:06:26.640
So, people are creating
businesses… basically.

02:06:26.720 --> 02:06:28.400
So, I think that will happen
more and more.

02:06:28.480 --> 02:06:32.720
Lots of online native sellers will come,
and they would have never known

02:06:32.800 --> 02:06:34.320
what does it mean to sell offline.

02:06:36.400 --> 02:06:39.720
I believe that… I can only…

02:06:40.640 --> 02:06:44.480
uh, finding the similarity
when we have started, let's say 2007-2008.

02:06:45.280 --> 02:06:48.200
The Internet at that time
was not even the main channel.

02:06:48.280 --> 02:06:51.200
Only eight million people having
the broadband and the Internet access

02:06:51.280 --> 02:06:52.720
at that time, 2008.

02:06:53.960 --> 02:06:57.680
Uh, but I think taking
that point to the Internet

02:06:57.760 --> 02:06:59.880
is the most powerful thing,
and people have evolved.

02:06:59.960 --> 02:07:02.320
Like social, I believe the 20-year guy

02:07:02.400 --> 02:07:04.360
will understand much better than me,

02:07:04.440 --> 02:07:07.080
and because when we have
to learn, talk to him.

02:07:07.680 --> 02:07:09.000
And finally, commerce,

02:07:09.080 --> 02:07:11.040
definitely doesn't matter which channel,

02:07:11.120 --> 02:07:14.560
but it is going to happen
and adopted in a most evolving way.

02:07:15.360 --> 02:07:19.440
I believe the social influencers
and all are a great channel.

02:07:19.520 --> 02:07:21.680
How to get use of that in…

02:07:21.760 --> 02:07:23.400
Look, I'm not talking about supply chain,

02:07:23.480 --> 02:07:25.360
I'm not talking about inventory.
Those are given.

02:07:25.880 --> 02:07:28.000
If you wanted to transport
one physical goods,

02:07:28.080 --> 02:07:29.600
those will come into play.

02:07:29.680 --> 02:07:32.600
And, somewhere, it's solving or solved,

02:07:32.680 --> 02:07:34.440
it's evolving in its own pace.

02:07:35.040 --> 02:07:39.600
But getting into the consumer side of it,
where the consumers' minds are,

02:07:39.680 --> 02:07:42.280
be part of that and see how…

02:07:42.360 --> 02:07:45.280
one can be… uh,
doing those commerce transactions,

02:07:45.960 --> 02:07:48.520
uh, how to influence.
I think that's the advice.

02:07:49.280 --> 02:07:52.000
And new channels already are emerging.

02:07:52.080 --> 02:07:53.080
[Nikhil] Super.

02:07:53.160 --> 02:07:54.160
Thank you, everyone, for watching.

02:07:54.240 --> 02:07:55.240
[Vidit] Thank you.

02:07:55.320 --> 02:07:56.920
Thank you, Kishore, Vidit and Sujeet.

02:07:57.000 --> 02:07:59.520
-Thanks… for hosting us.
-[Nikhil] Cheers, everyone.

02:07:59.600 --> 02:08:01.400
Hi, I'm Nikhil.

02:08:01.480 --> 02:08:03.760
Uh, thank you for watching the podcast.

02:08:04.280 --> 02:08:06.320
Let us know
who your favorite guest has been,

02:08:06.400 --> 02:08:08.440
and who you'd like to watch next.
Thank you.

